// notes/dl.js — TOPIC_CONTENT entries for the dl phase
Object.assign(TOPIC_CONTENT, {
  "dl_foundations": "<main>\n<h1>Neural Network Foundations</h1>\n\n<div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n  <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n  <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-perceptron\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The Perceptron</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Single neuron, linear boundary, why it's not enough</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-forward\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Forward Propagation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Layers, weights, activations \u2014 the full pass</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-backprop\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Backpropagation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Chain rule, gradients, why it works</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-activations\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Activation Functions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">ReLU, sigmoid, tanh, softmax \u2014 which and why</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-optimizers\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Optimizers</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">SGD, momentum, Adam, RMSprop \u2014 the math</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-regularization\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Regularization</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Dropout, batch norm, L1/L2 \u2014 what each actually does</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"dl-init\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Weight Initialization</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why random init matters, Xavier, He</span></div></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Perceptron:</strong> a single neuron computes a weighted sum of inputs plus a bias, then applies a step function. It can only draw a linear decision boundary \u2014 XOR is impossible. Stack perceptrons into layers and add non-linear activations and you get a universal function approximator.</li>\n    <li><strong>Forward pass:</strong> input \u2192 multiply by weight matrix \u2192 add bias \u2192 apply activation function \u2192 repeat for each layer \u2192 output. The network is computing a sequence of linear transformations interspersed with non-linearities. Without the non-linearities, any number of layers collapses to a single linear transformation \u2014 depth becomes meaningless.</li>\n    <li><strong>Backpropagation:</strong> compute the loss on the output, then use the chain rule to propagate gradients backward through every layer. Each weight receives a gradient telling it which direction to move to reduce the loss. This is not a special algorithm \u2014 it is just the chain rule of calculus applied recursively. PyTorch's autograd does this automatically.</li>\n    <li><strong>ReLU:</strong> max(0, x). Gradient is 1 for x > 0, 0 for x \u2264 0. Solves vanishing gradient for deep nets. Default activation for hidden layers. Dying ReLU problem: neurons that always receive negative input get zero gradient forever and stop learning. Fix: Leaky ReLU or ELU.</li>\n    <li><strong>Softmax:</strong> converts a vector of raw scores (logits) to a probability distribution that sums to 1. Used only in the final layer for multi-class classification. Never in hidden layers \u2014 it couples all activations together and destroys gradient flow.</li>\n    <li><strong>Adam:</strong> maintains a running average of past gradients (momentum) and past squared gradients (RMSProp). Adapts the learning rate per parameter. Default optimizer for almost everything. Can generalise worse than SGD on overparameterised networks because it finds sharper minima.</li>\n    <li><strong>Batch normalisation:</strong> normalises each layer's activations to zero mean and unit variance within a mini-batch, then lets the network learn the optimal scale and shift. Stabilises training, allows higher learning rates, acts as mild regularisation. Applied before the activation function in most implementations.</li>\n    <li><strong>Dropout:</strong> randomly zeroes a fraction p of neurons during each training forward pass. Forces the network to learn redundant representations \u2014 no single neuron can be relied upon. At inference, all neurons are on but outputs are scaled by (1\u2212p). Dropout in hidden layers: p=0.3\u20130.5. Never in batch-normalised layers \u2014 they conflict.</li>\n    <li><strong>Weight init:</strong> Xavier (Glorot) init for sigmoid/tanh \u2014 variance = 2/(fan_in + fan_out). He init for ReLU \u2014 variance = 2/fan_in. All-zero init fails: every neuron computes the same gradient and learns identically \u2014 symmetry breaking never happens.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. PERCEPTRON \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-perceptron\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>The Perceptron</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 the simplest possible model of a neuron</span>\n  <p>Before neural networks, classifiers were manually engineered feature pipelines. The perceptron was the first attempt to model how a biological neuron fires: accumulate weighted input signals, and fire if the total exceeds a threshold. The computational version: compute a weighted sum of inputs, output 1 if it exceeds a threshold, 0 otherwise. It can be trained automatically from data by adjusting weights whenever it makes a mistake.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the computation</span>\n  <p>Given inputs x = [x\u2081, x\u2082, ..., x\u2099], weights w = [w\u2081, w\u2082, ..., w\u2099], and bias b:<br><br>\n  <strong>z = w\u00b7x + b = \u03a3 w\u1d62x\u1d62 + b</strong><br><br>\n  Output: \u0177 = 1 if z \u2265 0, else 0 (step function).<br><br>\n  Training: if the perceptron makes an error on example (x, y), update w \u2190 w + \u03b1(y \u2212 \u0177)x. This is the perceptron learning rule \u2014 guaranteed to converge if the data is linearly separable.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 the perceptron cannot solve XOR, and why that matters</span>\n  <p>XOR: output 1 when inputs differ, 0 when they match. There is no single straight line that separates the XOR-positive points from the XOR-negative points in 2D space. The perceptron is a linear classifier \u2014 it can only draw hyperplanes. This was proven by Minsky and Papert in 1969, which killed AI funding for a decade (\"AI winter\").<br><br>\n  The fix: stack multiple perceptrons into layers. The first layer learns non-linear feature combinations; subsequent layers classify those features. Add non-linear activation functions between layers, and the network can approximate any continuous function \u2014 the Universal Approximation Theorem.</p>\n</div>\n\n<figure>\n  <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 180\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">Perceptron \u2192 MLP: adding layers solves the linearity problem</text>\n    <rect x=\"12\" y=\"28\" width=\"310\" height=\"140\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--red)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Single Perceptron</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">z = w\u00b7x + b \u2192 step function</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"90\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">One linear decision boundary</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Cannot solve XOR</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"126\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Cannot learn curves</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"144\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Limited to linearly separable data</text>\n    <rect x=\"378\" y=\"28\" width=\"310\" height=\"140\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Stacked layers + non-linear activations</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"90\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Each layer learns more abstract features</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Solves XOR (2 layers sufficient)</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"126\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Universal function approximator</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"144\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Learns any continuous function</text>\n  </svg>\n</figure>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. FORWARD PASS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-forward\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Forward Propagation</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 how a network makes a prediction</span>\n  <p>A neural network is a function: given an input, produce an output. Forward propagation is the mechanism of that function \u2014 data flows forward through layers, each layer transforming it, until the final layer produces a prediction. Understanding this precisely is prerequisite to understanding backprop, because backprop is just forward prop in reverse.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the computation at each layer</span>\n  <p>For layer l with weight matrix W\u02e1, bias b\u02e1, and activation function \u03c3:<br><br>\n  <strong>z\u02e1 = W\u02e1 \u00b7 a\u02e1\u207b\u00b9 + b\u02e1</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp; (linear transformation)<br>\n  <strong>a\u02e1 = \u03c3(z\u02e1)</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (non-linear activation)<br><br>\n  Where a\u02e1\u207b\u00b9 is the activation from the previous layer (a\u2070 = input x). z is called the pre-activation or logit. a is the post-activation. The final layer's activation is the network's prediction \u0177.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW \u2014 what each layer is actually learning</span>\n  <p>In a network trained on images: layer 1 learns to detect edges (horizontal, vertical, diagonal lines). Layer 2 combines edges into textures and corners. Layer 3 combines textures into object parts (eyes, wheels). Final layers combine parts into whole objects.<br><br>\n  This hierarchical feature learning is the key insight \u2014 each layer builds representations on top of the previous layer's representations. Deeper networks learn more abstract features. The \"learning\" is just the weight matrix W\u02e1 at each layer \u2014 training finds the weight values that produce useful representations.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 without non-linearities, depth is useless</span>\n  <p>If every layer is just a linear transformation with no activation function: W\u02e1(W\u02e1\u207b\u00b9(...(W\u00b9x))) = (W\u02e1W\u02e1\u207b\u00b9...W\u00b9)x = Wx. Any number of linear layers collapses to a single linear transformation. A 100-layer network without activations is identical to a 1-layer network. Depth only gains you expressive power through non-linear activations between layers.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. BACKPROP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-backprop\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Backpropagation</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 the algorithm that makes training possible</span>\n  <p>After a forward pass, the network makes a prediction and we compute a loss (how wrong it was). To improve, every weight in the network needs a gradient: which direction should this weight move to reduce the loss? With millions of weights, computing each gradient independently is computationally impossible. Backpropagation computes all gradients in one backward pass through the network using the chain rule \u2014 efficiently, in O(weights) time.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the chain rule applied recursively</span>\n  <p>The chain rule: if L depends on z, and z depends on w, then \u2202L/\u2202w = (\u2202L/\u2202z)(\u2202z/\u2202w).<br><br>\n  Backprop applies this recursively from the output layer to the input layer:<br><br>\n  <strong>Step 1:</strong> compute \u2202L/\u2202\u0177 \u2014 gradient of loss w.r.t. network output (easy, loss function is simple).<br>\n  <strong>Step 2:</strong> propagate to final layer: \u2202L/\u2202W\u02e1 = (\u2202L/\u2202a\u02e1)(\u2202a\u02e1/\u2202z\u02e1)(\u2202z\u02e1/\u2202W\u02e1)<br>\n  <strong>Step 3:</strong> compute \u2202L/\u2202a\u02e1\u207b\u00b9 to pass the gradient to the previous layer.<br>\n  <strong>Step 4:</strong> repeat steps 2\u20133 all the way back to layer 1.<br><br>\n  Each layer only needs the gradient arriving from the layer above \u2014 it never needs to see the whole network. This locality is what makes backprop efficient.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 blame propagation through a chain of decisions</span>\n  <p>A manager makes a bad decision. Their decision was based on a report from a department head. That report was based on data from an analyst. When the bad outcome is discovered, you trace blame backwards: how much did the final decision cause the outcome? How much did the report cause the final decision? How much did the analyst's data cause the report?<br><br>\n  Backprop does exactly this. The loss is the bad outcome. Every weight's gradient is its \"share of the blame.\" The chain rule lets you compute each weight's blame precisely by working backwards through the chain of computations that produced the prediction.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW \u2014 what PyTorch autograd does for you</span>\n  <p>You never implement backprop manually. PyTorch builds a computation graph during the forward pass \u2014 every operation records which tensors it used and how. When you call <code>loss.backward()</code>, PyTorch traverses this graph in reverse, computing gradients for every tensor that has <code>requires_grad=True</code>. The gradients accumulate in <code>tensor.grad</code>. Then the optimizer reads those gradients and updates the weights.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n\n<span class=\"c\"># A simple 2-layer network</span>\nmodel = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(<span class=\"y\">10</span>, <span class=\"y\">64</span>),\n    nn.ReLU(),\n    nn.Linear(<span class=\"y\">64</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>)\n)\nloss_fn  = nn.MSELoss()\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>)\n\nx = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># batch of 32</span>\ny = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 1. Forward pass \u2014 builds computation graph</span>\npred = model(x)\nloss = loss_fn(pred, y)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 2. Backward pass \u2014 computes all gradients via chain rule</span>\noptimizer.zero_grad()   <span class=\"c\"># clear gradients from previous step (they accumulate)</span>\nloss.backward()         <span class=\"c\"># \u2202loss/\u2202w for every weight in model</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 3. Update weights</span>\noptimizer.step()        <span class=\"c\"># w \u2190 w \u2212 lr \u00d7 grad</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Inspect gradient of first layer's weight</span>\nprint(model[<span class=\"y\">0</span>].weight.grad.shape)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 torch.Size([64, 10])</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 vanishing and exploding gradients</span>\n  <p><strong>Vanishing:</strong> gradients are products of many numbers. If each layer's gradient is &lt;1 (sigmoid saturates to near-zero gradient at extremes), the product shrinks exponentially with depth. By layer 1, the gradient is \u2248 0 \u2014 early layers stop learning. This killed deep networks before ReLU and batch norm.<br><br>\n  <strong>Exploding:</strong> if gradients are consistently &gt;1, the product grows exponentially. Weights update by enormous amounts, training diverges. Fix: gradient clipping (<code>torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0)</code>).<br><br>\n  Both problems are why weight initialisation, activation function choice, and batch normalisation matter \u2014 they keep gradients in a healthy range throughout the network.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. ACTIVATIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-activations\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Activation Functions</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 non-linearity is everything</span>\n  <p>Without activation functions, neural networks are linear models regardless of depth. Activation functions introduce non-linearity after each linear transformation, enabling the network to learn curved decision boundaries and complex feature hierarchies. The choice of activation function directly affects gradient flow, training speed, and whether deep networks can be trained at all.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the four activations you need to know deeply</span>\n  <p><strong>Sigmoid:</strong> \u03c3(x) = 1/(1+e\u207b\u02e3). Output \u2208 (0,1). Gradient = \u03c3(x)(1\u2212\u03c3(x)), maximum 0.25 at x=0. Saturates to near-zero gradient at both extremes \u2014 causes vanishing gradients in deep networks. Only use in the final layer for binary classification.<br><br>\n  <strong>Tanh:</strong> tanh(x) = (e\u02e3\u2212e\u207b\u02e3)/(e\u02e3+e\u207b\u02e3). Output \u2208 (\u22121,1). Zero-centred (sigmoid isn't). Gradient maximum 1.0 at x=0. Still saturates. Better than sigmoid for hidden layers but ReLU dominates in practice.<br><br>\n  <strong>ReLU:</strong> f(x) = max(0,x). Gradient = 1 for x>0, 0 for x\u22640. No saturation for positive inputs. Computationally cheap. Default for hidden layers in almost everything. Problem: dying ReLU \u2014 neurons with permanently negative pre-activations get zero gradient forever and never recover.<br><br>\n  <strong>Softmax:</strong> \u03c3(z)\u1d62 = e\u1dbb\u2071 / \u03a3\u2c7c e\u1dbb\u02b2. Converts a vector of logits to a probability distribution summing to 1. Only for the final output layer in multi-class classification. Never in hidden layers.</p>\n</div>\n\n<figure>\n  <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 200\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">Activation functions \u2014 shape, range, and gradient behaviour</text>\n    <!-- Sigmoid -->\n    <rect x=\"12\" y=\"28\" width=\"155\" height=\"160\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"var(--blue-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--border-s)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">Sigmoid</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">\u03c3(x) = 1/(1+e\u207b\u02e3)</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Range: (0, 1)</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Prob output</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Vanishes deep</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Not zero-centred</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"155\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">Use: final layer</text>\n    <text x=\"89\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">binary classification</text>\n    <!-- Tanh -->\n    <rect x=\"181\" y=\"28\" width=\"155\" height=\"160\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"var(--teal-dim)\" stroke=\"rgba(8,145,178,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--teal)\">Tanh</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">(e\u02e3\u2212e\u207b\u02e3)/(e\u02e3+e\u207b\u02e3)</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Range: (\u22121, 1)</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Zero-centred</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Still saturates</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 ReLU beats it</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"155\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--teal)\">Use: LSTMs, GRUs</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--teal)\">(specific architectures)</text>\n    <!-- ReLU -->\n    <rect x=\"350\" y=\"28\" width=\"155\" height=\"160\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"rgba(5,150,105,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">ReLU</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">f(x) = max(0, x)</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Range: [0, \u221e)</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 No saturation (x>0)</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Fast, sparse</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Dying ReLU</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"155\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Use: all hidden layers</text>\n    <text x=\"427\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">default choice</text>\n    <!-- Softmax -->\n    <rect x=\"519\" y=\"28\" width=\"169\" height=\"160\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"var(--violet-dim)\" stroke=\"rgba(124,58,237,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">Softmax</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">e\u1dbb\u2071 / \u03a3 e\u1dbb\u02b2</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Range: (0,1), sums to 1</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">\u2713 Prob distribution</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Final layer only</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">\u2717 Kills gradient flow</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"155\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">Use: final layer</text>\n    <text x=\"603\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">multi-class only</text>\n  </svg>\n</figure>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 dying ReLU and how to fix it</span>\n  <p>A ReLU neuron \"dies\" when its pre-activation z is negative for every input in the dataset. Gradient at z\u22640 is zero \u2014 the neuron receives no gradient signal and its weights never update. It's permanently off. This can happen when weights are initialised badly or the learning rate is too high (large negative updates push many neurons below zero simultaneously).<br><br>\n  Fixes: <strong>Leaky ReLU</strong> \u2014 f(x) = x if x>0, 0.01x if x\u22640. Small gradient even for negative inputs. <strong>ELU</strong> \u2014 smooth negative region, negative outputs help push mean activations toward zero. <strong>He initialisation</strong> (see section 07) \u2014 keeps initial activations in a healthy range. In practice: Leaky ReLU is often sufficient.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">INTERVIEW ANGLE \u2014 \"why not use sigmoid in hidden layers?\"</span>\n  <p>Strong answer: \"Sigmoid squashes inputs to (0,1). Its gradient is \u03c3(x)(1\u2212\u03c3(x)), which has a maximum of 0.25 at x=0 and approaches zero at both extremes. In a deep network, backprop multiplies these gradients across layers \u2014 the product of many numbers less than 0.25 vanishes exponentially. By the time the gradient reaches early layers, it is essentially zero and those layers stop learning. ReLU avoids this: its gradient is exactly 1 for all positive inputs, so gradients flow through without shrinking. This is the primary reason deep networks became trainable \u2014 switch from sigmoid to ReLU hidden activations.\"</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. OPTIMIZERS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-optimizers\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Optimizers</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 gradient descent alone is too slow and unstable</span>\n  <p>Basic gradient descent: w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u2207L. This uses a fixed learning rate for every parameter at every step. Problem: the loss landscape is highly non-uniform. Some directions are steep (need small steps), others are flat (need large steps). Some parameters need frequent large updates; others need rare small ones. A single fixed learning rate is wrong for all of them simultaneously. Optimizers add heuristics on top of gradient descent to adapt the effective learning rate per parameter over time.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 SGD, Momentum, RMSprop, Adam</span>\n  <p><strong>SGD (Stochastic Gradient Descent):</strong> w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u00b7g, where g = gradient on a mini-batch. \"Stochastic\" because you use a random subset (batch) rather than all data. Noisy \u2014 each step uses an approximation to the true gradient. The noise is actually beneficial: it helps escape sharp local minima and often finds flatter, more generalisable solutions.<br><br>\n  <strong>Momentum:</strong> v \u2190 \u03b2v + (1\u2212\u03b2)g, then w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1v. Maintains a running average of past gradients. Smooths out noise \u2014 consistent gradient directions accumulate speed; inconsistent (noisy) directions cancel out. \u03b2=0.9 is standard. Analogy: a ball rolling downhill builds momentum, overshoots small bumps, settles in valleys.<br><br>\n  <strong>RMSprop:</strong> v \u2190 \u03b2\u2082v + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2082)g\u00b2, then w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u00b7g/\u221a(v+\u03b5). Divides each parameter's gradient by the root of its recent squared gradient history. Parameters with large recent gradients get smaller steps; parameters with small gradients get larger steps. Adapts learning rate per parameter. Good for RNNs.<br><br>\n  <strong>Adam (Adaptive Moment Estimation):</strong> combines momentum (first moment m) and RMSprop (second moment v). m \u2190 \u03b2\u2081m + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2081)g. v \u2190 \u03b2\u2082v + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2082)g\u00b2. Bias correction: m\u0302 = m/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2081\u1d57), v\u0302 = v/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2082\u1d57). Update: w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u00b7m\u0302/(\u221av\u0302+\u03b5). \u03b2\u2081=0.9, \u03b2\u2082=0.999, \u03b5=1e-8, \u03b1=0.001 are near-universal defaults.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 navigating a hilly landscape in fog</span>\n  <p>SGD: you can only feel the slope under your feet. You take a step downhill. You might oscillate in narrow valleys because each step overshoots.<br><br>\n  Momentum: you're a ball. You built up speed in the direction you've been going. You roll through small bumps instead of stopping at every dip.<br><br>\n  RMSprop: you have a map showing where the terrain changes quickly vs slowly. In steep areas you take small cautious steps. In flat areas you take large confident steps.<br><br>\n  Adam: both \u2014 you have built-up directional momentum AND a map of terrain steepness. You move fast in consistent flat directions and cautiously in steep erratic ones.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 Adam generalises worse than SGD for large models</span>\n  <p>Adam converges faster but often to sharper minima. Research consistently shows that SGD with momentum finds flatter loss landscape minima that generalise better \u2014 especially for large overparameterised models (ResNets, Transformers). The intuition: Adam's adaptive learning rates suppress gradient noise, which sounds good but actually removes a useful regularisation signal. SGD's noise steers training away from sharp narrow minima toward wide flat ones.<br><br>\n  In practice: use Adam for fast experimentation and when training time matters. If you have time to tune, SGD+momentum often wins final accuracy. Many state-of-the-art image models use SGD with cosine annealing LR schedule. Transformers almost universally use AdamW (Adam with decoupled weight decay).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.optim <span class=\"k\">as</span> optim\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Adam \u2014 default choice for most tasks</span>\noptimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>, weight_decay=<span class=\"y\">1e-4</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># AdamW \u2014 Adam with decoupled weight decay (correct L2 regularisation)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Standard for Transformers. Use this instead of Adam when using weight decay.</span>\noptimizer = optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>, weight_decay=<span class=\"y\">0.01</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># SGD + momentum \u2014 often better generalisation for CNNs</span>\noptimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">0.01</span>, momentum=<span class=\"y\">0.9</span>, weight_decay=<span class=\"y\">1e-4</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Learning rate scheduling \u2014 reduce LR when training plateaus</span>\nscheduler = optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=<span class=\"y\">100</span>)\n<span class=\"c\"># Or reduce on plateau:</span>\nscheduler = optim.lr_scheduler.ReduceLROnPlateau(optimizer, patience=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, factor=<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Gradient clipping \u2014 prevents exploding gradients (essential for RNNs)</span>\nloss.backward()\ntorch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>)\noptimizer.step()\nscheduler.step(val_loss)  <span class=\"c\"># ReduceLROnPlateau needs the metric</span></div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. REGULARIZATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-regularization\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Regularization \u2014 Dropout and Batch Norm</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 neural networks overfit aggressively</span>\n  <p>A large neural network has millions of parameters. Given enough capacity, it can memorise the training set exactly \u2014 zero training loss, terrible test performance. Regularisation techniques reduce this overfitting by constraining what the network can learn during training, either by adding noise, penalising complexity, or normalising activations.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 Dropout</span>\n  <p>During each training forward pass, randomly set each neuron's activation to zero with probability p (typically 0.3\u20130.5). The zeroed neurons don't contribute to the output and receive no gradient update for that step.<br><br>\n  At inference: all neurons are active, but their outputs are multiplied by (1\u2212p) to keep the expected magnitude consistent with training. PyTorch's <code>nn.Dropout</code> handles this automatically \u2014 outputs are scaled during training by 1/(1\u2212p) so inference requires no scaling (inverted dropout).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW Dropout works \u2014 the ensemble interpretation</span>\n  <p>With dropout p=0.5, each forward pass uses a different random subset of neurons \u2014 effectively a different network architecture. Over training, you train an exponential number of different sub-networks that share weights. At inference, you run all neurons (scaled) \u2014 which approximates averaging the predictions of all those sub-networks. Dropout is cheap ensemble learning baked into a single model.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 Batch Normalisation</span>\n  <p>After the linear transformation (before the activation), normalise the activations within each mini-batch to zero mean and unit variance, then learn a scale \u03b3 and shift \u03b2 per feature:<br><br>\n  \u03bc_B = mean of z\u02e1 across batch. \u03c3\u00b2_B = variance. z\u0303 = (z \u2212 \u03bc_B)/\u221a(\u03c3\u00b2_B + \u03b5). output = \u03b3z\u0303 + \u03b2<br><br>\n  At inference: use running estimates of mean and variance accumulated during training (not the current batch statistics).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW BatchNorm helps training \u2014 three mechanisms</span>\n  <p><strong>1. Reduces internal covariate shift:</strong> as earlier layers' weights update, the distribution of inputs to later layers keeps changing \u2014 layers must constantly re-adapt. BatchNorm re-centres every layer's input distribution, stabilising what later layers see.<br><br>\n  <strong>2. Allows higher learning rates:</strong> without BatchNorm, high LRs cause activations to saturate or explode. With normalised activations, you can use 10\u00d7 higher LRs and train faster.<br><br>\n  <strong>3. Mild regularisation:</strong> using batch statistics introduces noise (each mini-batch has slightly different statistics). This acts like dropout \u2014 mild regularisation that sometimes makes explicit dropout unnecessary in BatchNorm'd architectures.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 never use Dropout and BatchNorm together in the same layer</span>\n  <p>BatchNorm uses batch statistics to normalise. Dropout randomly zeros neurons. When dropout is applied before BatchNorm, the statistics computed by BatchNorm are based on a randomly thinned batch \u2014 the mean and variance estimates are noisy and inconsistent between training and inference. This causes a train/test discrepancy that hurts performance.<br><br>\n  Rule: if you use BatchNorm, use dropout only after it, not before. In practice: modern ResNets use BatchNorm but no dropout. Dropout is preferred in fully-connected layers and older architectures without BatchNorm.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Standard modern block: Linear \u2192 BatchNorm \u2192 ReLU \u2192 Dropout</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># BatchNorm before activation (most common)</span>\nblock = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(<span class=\"y\">256</span>, <span class=\"y\">256</span>),\n    nn.BatchNorm1d(<span class=\"y\">256</span>),   <span class=\"c\"># normalise across batch dimension</span>\n    nn.ReLU(),\n    nn.Dropout(p=<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># AFTER BatchNorm, not before</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># model.train() vs model.eval() \u2014 critical distinction</span>\nmodel.train()   <span class=\"c\"># Dropout active, BatchNorm uses batch statistics</span>\nmodel.eval()    <span class=\"c\"># Dropout disabled, BatchNorm uses running statistics</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Forgetting model.eval() during validation is one of the most common bugs in DL</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># L2 regularisation \u2014 passed as weight_decay to optimizer (not as a layer)</span>\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>, weight_decay=<span class=\"y\">1e-4</span>)\n<span class=\"c\"># weight_decay adds \u03bb||w||\u00b2 to loss \u2014 equivalent to L2 penalty</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 forgetting model.eval() is the most common DL bug</span>\n  <p>If you forget to call <code>model.eval()</code> before validation or inference: dropout randomly zeroes neurons during evaluation \u2014 your validation loss fluctuates randomly and is not reproducible. BatchNorm uses noisy batch statistics instead of stable running estimates \u2014 accuracy degrades. Always: <code>model.train()</code> before training loop, <code>model.eval()</code> before any evaluation, and wrap inference in <code>with torch.no_grad():</code> to disable gradient computation.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 07. WEIGHT INIT \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-init\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Weight Initialisation</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 initialisation determines whether training starts at all</span>\n  <p>Weights must be initialised before training. The choice has dramatic consequences: wrong initialisation causes vanishing or exploding activations from the very first forward pass, before any gradient has been computed. The network can fail to learn anything even with a correct architecture and good data.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the three initialisation schemes</span>\n  <p><strong>Zero init:</strong> all weights = 0. Every neuron in a layer computes the same output, receives the same gradient, and updates identically. Symmetry is never broken \u2014 all neurons in a layer remain identical forever. The network never differentiates. Never use zero init for weights (biases can be zero).<br><br>\n  <strong>Xavier (Glorot) init:</strong> sample weights from uniform or normal distribution with variance = 2/(fan_in + fan_out), where fan_in = number of input connections, fan_out = number of output connections. Keeps activation variance roughly constant across layers for sigmoid/tanh activations.<br><br>\n  <strong>He (Kaiming) init:</strong> variance = 2/fan_in. Designed specifically for ReLU \u2014 accounts for the fact that ReLU zeros out half the neurons, effectively halving the signal. Use He init whenever your hidden layers use ReLU or Leaky ReLU.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW \u2014 why variance matters layer by layer</span>\n  <p>If each weight is too large: activations grow exponentially with depth \u2014 layer 10 has values in the millions, sigmoid saturates, gradients vanish. If weights are too small: activations shrink to zero \u2014 the network has no signal to learn from.<br><br>\n  Xavier and He init choose the variance such that the expected activation magnitude stays roughly constant as data flows forward through the network \u2014 keeping each layer in the \"useful range\" of its activation function.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n\n<span class=\"c\"># PyTorch default initialisation is already good</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Linear layers: Kaiming uniform by default (suitable for ReLU)</span>\nlayer = nn.Linear(<span class=\"y\">256</span>, <span class=\"y\">128</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># already He-initialised</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Explicit initialisation if you need control</span>\nnn.init.kaiming_normal_(layer.weight, nonlinearity=<span class=\"g\">'relu'</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># He for ReLU</span>\nnn.init.xavier_normal_(layer.weight)                          <span class=\"c\"># Xavier for sigmoid/tanh</span>\nnn.init.zeros_(layer.bias)                                     <span class=\"c\"># bias always zero</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Apply to all layers in a model</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">init_weights</span>(m):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> isinstance(m, nn.Linear):\n        nn.init.kaiming_normal_(m.weight, nonlinearity=<span class=\"g\">'relu'</span>)\n        nn.init.zeros_(m.bias)\n    <span class=\"k\">elif</span> isinstance(m, nn.Conv2d):\n        nn.init.kaiming_normal_(m.weight, mode=<span class=\"g\">'fan_out'</span>, nonlinearity=<span class=\"g\">'relu'</span>)\n\nmodel.apply(init_weights)</div>\n\n<!-- Q&A -->\n<h2 id=\"dl-qa\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n<div class=\"qa-head\">\n  <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n  <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n</div>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is backpropagation and why is it efficient?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Backpropagation is the application of the chain rule of calculus to compute gradients of the loss with respect to every weight in the network. After a forward pass computes the loss, backprop traverses the computation graph in reverse \u2014 from output to input. Each layer receives the gradient from the layer above, multiplies it by its local gradient (how its output changes w.r.t. its input and weights), and passes the result further back. Efficiency: each weight's gradient requires O(1) operations given the gradient arriving from the next layer. Total cost is O(weights) \u2014 same as one forward pass. Without this, computing each weight's gradient independently would require O(weights\u00b2) operations.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does ReLU work better than sigmoid for deep networks?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Two reasons. First: sigmoid gradient = \u03c3(x)(1\u2212\u03c3(x)), maximum 0.25 at x=0, approaching zero at both tails. In a 10-layer network, backprop multiplies these gradients \u2014 0.25\u00b9\u2070 \u2248 0.000001. Early layers receive essentially zero gradient and stop learning (vanishing gradient). ReLU gradient is exactly 1 for all positive inputs \u2014 no shrinkage in the positive regime. Second: ReLU is computationally trivial (max(0,x)) vs sigmoid's exponential, making both forward and backward passes faster. Downside: dying ReLU \u2014 neurons that always receive negative input get zero gradient permanently. Fixed with Leaky ReLU (small negative slope instead of zero).</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What does batch normalisation actually do and why does it help?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">BatchNorm normalises each layer's pre-activation output to zero mean and unit variance within a mini-batch, then learns a per-feature scale \u03b3 and shift \u03b2. Three benefits: (1) Reduces internal covariate shift \u2014 as earlier layers update, the distribution of inputs to later layers shifts constantly. BatchNorm re-centres each layer's input, stabilising training. (2) Allows much higher learning rates \u2014 normalised activations are less likely to explode or saturate, so you can train faster. (3) Acts as mild regularisation \u2014 batch statistics vary slightly per mini-batch, introducing noise similar to dropout. Critical implementation detail: model.eval() switches BatchNorm from using batch statistics to stored running statistics \u2014 forgetting this causes subtle accuracy drops at inference.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When would you choose SGD over Adam?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Adam converges faster but often to sharper minima that generalise worse, especially in overparameterised models. SGD with momentum's gradient noise acts as implicit regularisation, steering training toward flatter minima. In practice: CNNs for image classification (ResNets) often achieve better final accuracy with SGD + momentum + cosine LR schedule than Adam, at the cost of requiring more careful LR tuning. Adam is better when you need fast convergence, are experimenting with architectures, or training Transformers (where AdamW is standard because weight decay interacts correctly with Adam's adaptive learning rates). Rule of thumb: Adam for experimentation and NLP/Transformers; SGD+momentum for final CNN training when squeezing out last accuracy percent.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "dl_pytorch": "<main>\n<h1>PyTorch \u2014 Priority Framework</h1>\n\n<div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n  <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n  <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-tensors\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Tensors</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The fundamental data structure \u2014 shape, dtype, device</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-autograd\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Autograd</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Automatic differentiation \u2014 how gradients are computed</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-module\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">nn.Module</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Building custom models \u2014 the right way</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-data\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Datasets &amp; DataLoaders</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Efficient data pipelines, batching, augmentation</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-training\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Training Loop</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The complete pattern \u2014 every step explained</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-gpu\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">GPU Training</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">CUDA, device management, mixed precision</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-transfer\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Transfer Learning</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Fine-tuning pretrained models \u2014 freeze and unfreeze</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pt-checkpoint\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Saving &amp; Loading</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Checkpoints, state dicts, resuming training</span></div></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Tensor:</strong> PyTorch's n-dimensional array. Three critical attributes: shape (dimensions), dtype (float32/int64/bool), device (cpu/cuda). Operations between tensors on different devices fail \u2014 always move to the same device first. Tensors with requires_grad=True track their computation history for autograd.</li>\n    <li><strong>Autograd:</strong> PyTorch builds a computation graph during the forward pass. Every tensor operation records which tensors it used. loss.backward() traverses this graph in reverse computing \u2202loss/\u2202w for every tensor with requires_grad=True. Gradients accumulate in .grad \u2014 you must call optimizer.zero_grad() before each backward pass or gradients from previous steps accumulate.</li>\n    <li><strong>nn.Module:</strong> base class for all neural network layers and models. Defines __init__ (register layers as attributes) and forward() (computation). Calling model(x) invokes forward(). Parameters registered inside __init__ are automatically tracked by optimizers and moved by .to(device).</li>\n    <li><strong>DataLoader:</strong> wraps a Dataset, handles batching, shuffling, and parallel data loading (num_workers). The Dataset defines __len__ and __getitem__. Never put heavy preprocessing inside __getitem__ on the main process \u2014 use transforms and num_workers to parallelise.</li>\n    <li><strong>Training loop order:</strong> zero_grad \u2192 forward \u2192 compute loss \u2192 backward \u2192 (clip gradients) \u2192 optimizer step \u2192 (scheduler step). This exact order matters. Deviating causes subtle bugs.</li>\n    <li><strong>.to(device) vs .cuda():</strong> always use .to(device) where device = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\"). Hardcoding .cuda() breaks on machines without GPUs.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transfer learning:</strong> load pretrained weights \u2192 freeze all layers (requires_grad=False) \u2192 replace final layer with new head for your task \u2192 unfreeze and fine-tune gradually. Fine-tuning with a low LR (1e-4 to 1e-5) on the pretrained layers; higher LR on the new head.</li>\n    <li><strong>Save the state_dict, not the model:</strong> torch.save(model.state_dict(), path). Load with model.load_state_dict(torch.load(path)). Saving the whole model object breaks when class definitions change. State dict is just a dict of parameter tensors \u2014 portable and stable.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. TENSORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-tensors\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Tensors</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 PyTorch's fundamental data structure</span>\n  <p>A tensor is an n-dimensional array. Scalars are 0-d tensors. Vectors are 1-d. Matrices are 2-d. In deep learning: a batch of 32 images of size 224\u00d7224 with 3 colour channels is a 4-d tensor of shape (32, 3, 224, 224). Every piece of data in PyTorch \u2014 inputs, weights, gradients, outputs \u2014 is a tensor.</p>\n  <p>Three attributes define a tensor completely:<br>\n  <strong>shape</strong> \u2014 dimensions, e.g. (32, 3, 224, 224)<br>\n  <strong>dtype</strong> \u2014 float32 (default for neural nets), float16, int64, bool<br>\n  <strong>device</strong> \u2014 cpu or cuda:0 (which GPU)</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 device mismatch is the most common PyTorch error</span>\n  <p>Operations between tensors on different devices raise RuntimeError immediately. Your model is on GPU, your batch is on CPU \u2014 the forward pass fails. Systematic fix: define device = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\") once at the top. Move the model with model.to(device). Move every batch with x, y = x.to(device), y.to(device) inside the DataLoader loop. Never use .cuda() directly \u2014 it breaks on CPU-only machines.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Creating tensors</span>\nx = torch.tensor([<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>, <span class=\"y\">2.0</span>, <span class=\"y\">3.0</span>])              <span class=\"c\"># from Python list</span>\nx = torch.zeros(<span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>)                            <span class=\"c\"># 3\u00d74 of zeros</span>\nx = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">224</span>, <span class=\"y\">224</span>)               <span class=\"c\"># random normal \u2014 simulate a batch</span>\nx = torch.arange(<span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>, step=<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>)              <span class=\"c\"># like np.arange</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Shape operations \u2014 reshaping without copying data</span>\nx = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">784</span>)\nx.view(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">28</span>, <span class=\"y\">28</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># requires contiguous memory</span>\nx.reshape(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">28</span>, <span class=\"y\">28</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># safe: copies if needed</span>\nx.squeeze(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)               <span class=\"c\"># remove dimension of size 1</span>\nx.unsqueeze(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)             <span class=\"c\"># add dimension of size 1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Device management \u2014 always use this pattern</span>\ndevice = torch.device(<span class=\"g\">\"cuda\"</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> torch.cuda.is_available() <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"g\">\"cpu\"</span>)\nx = x.to(device)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Conversion</span>\nx_numpy = x.cpu().numpy()          <span class=\"c\"># must be on CPU first</span>\nx_tensor = torch.from_numpy(arr)   <span class=\"c\"># shares memory \u2014 modifying one modifies both</span></div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. AUTOGRAD \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-autograd\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Autograd \u2014 Automatic Differentiation</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY and WHAT</span>\n  <p>Autograd is PyTorch's engine for automatic gradient computation. Any tensor with requires_grad=True participates in gradient tracking. During the forward pass, every operation on such a tensor is recorded in a dynamic computation graph. When you call .backward() on the loss, PyTorch traverses this graph in reverse \u2014 the chain rule applied automatically to every recorded operation.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW \u2014 the computation graph is dynamic</span>\n  <p>Unlike TensorFlow 1.x which defined a static graph before running, PyTorch builds the graph on the fly during each forward pass. This means Python control flow (if statements, loops, dynamic shapes) works naturally \u2014 the graph reflects exactly what happened in that specific forward pass. Different inputs can produce different graph structures. This is why PyTorch is dominant in research: you can write normal Python and it just works.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Manually demonstrating autograd</span>\nx = torch.tensor(<span class=\"y\">3.0</span>, requires_grad=<span class=\"y\">True</span>)\ny = x ** <span class=\"y\">2</span> + <span class=\"y\">2</span> * x   <span class=\"c\"># y = x\u00b2 + 2x, dy/dx = 2x + 2</span>\ny.backward()           <span class=\"c\"># compute dy/dx</span>\nprint(x.grad)          <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 tensor(8.) because 2(3) + 2 = 8 \u2713</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Stopping gradient tracking \u2014 3 contexts</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 1. torch.no_grad() \u2014 for inference, disables graph building, saves memory</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> torch.no_grad():\n    pred = model(x_test)   <span class=\"c\"># no graph built, much faster</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 2. .detach() \u2014 create a new tensor that shares data but has no grad</span>\ntarget = model_output.detach()  <span class=\"c\"># used to stop gradient flow in part of a chain</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 3. requires_grad=False \u2014 freeze a parameter permanently</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> param <span class=\"k\">in</span> model.encoder.parameters():\n    param.requires_grad = <span class=\"y\">False</span>   <span class=\"c\"># frozen \u2014 no gradient, no update</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Critical: zero_grad() before each backward pass</span>\noptimizer.zero_grad()   <span class=\"c\"># PyTorch accumulates gradients \u2014 must clear manually</span>\nloss.backward()\noptimizer.step()</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 gradients accumulate by default</span>\n  <p>PyTorch adds to .grad rather than replacing it. If you call backward() twice without zeroing, gradients from both passes sum together. This is intentional for gradient accumulation (simulating larger batch sizes), but for normal training it means forgetting zero_grad() causes wrong updates from the very first step. Always: zero_grad \u2192 forward \u2192 loss \u2192 backward \u2192 step. In that exact order, every iteration.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. NN.MODULE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-module\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>nn.Module \u2014 Building Models</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the base class for everything in PyTorch</span>\n  <p>Every neural network layer (Linear, Conv2d, BatchNorm) and every custom model inherits from nn.Module. It provides: automatic parameter registration (anything assigned as an attribute in __init__ that is itself an nn.Module or nn.Parameter is tracked), .to(device) that recursively moves all parameters, .train()/.eval() that recursively sets mode, and .parameters() that returns all trainable parameters for the optimizer.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn.functional <span class=\"k\">as</span> F\n\n<span class=\"c\"># The correct way to define a model</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">MLPClassifier</span>(nn.Module):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, input_dim, hidden_dim, num_classes, dropout=<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">super</span>().__init__()          <span class=\"c\"># MUST call super().__init__() first</span>\n\n        <span class=\"c\"># Layers registered as attributes \u2014 autograd and .to() track them</span>\n        self.fc1    = nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_dim)\n        self.bn1    = nn.BatchNorm1d(hidden_dim)\n        self.drop1  = nn.Dropout(p=dropout)\n        self.fc2    = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, hidden_dim // <span class=\"y\">2</span>)\n        self.fc_out = nn.Linear(hidden_dim // <span class=\"y\">2</span>, num_classes)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">forward</span>(self, x):\n        <span class=\"c\"># Define the computation \u2014 called by model(x)</span>\n        x = self.fc1(x)\n        x = self.bn1(x)\n        x = F.relu(x)          <span class=\"c\"># functional API for stateless ops</span>\n        x = self.drop1(x)\n        x = F.relu(self.fc2(x))\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.fc_out(x)  <span class=\"c\"># raw logits \u2014 loss function applies softmax</span>\n\nmodel = MLPClassifier(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">784</span>, hidden_dim=<span class=\"y\">256</span>, num_classes=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\nmodel = model.to(device)   <span class=\"c\"># moves ALL parameters to device recursively</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Inspect model</span>\nprint(model)               <span class=\"c\"># shows layer structure</span>\ntotal_params = sum(p.numel() <span class=\"k\">for</span> p <span class=\"k\">in</span> model.parameters())\ntrainable    = sum(p.numel() <span class=\"k\">for</span> p <span class=\"k\">in</span> model.parameters() <span class=\"k\">if</span> p.requires_grad)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Total: {total_params:,} | Trainable: {trainable:,}\"</span>)</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. DATA \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-data\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Datasets &amp; DataLoaders</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY and WHAT</span>\n  <p>Training requires feeding data in batches, shuffled, efficiently. Dataset defines what data exists and how to load one item. DataLoader wraps a Dataset, handles batching (stacking items into tensors), shuffling, and parallelising data loading across multiple CPU workers so GPU is never starved waiting for data.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> torch.utils.data <span class=\"k\">import</span> Dataset, DataLoader\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> torchvision <span class=\"k\">import</span> transforms\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pandas <span class=\"k\">as</span> pd\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> torch\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Custom Dataset \u2014 implement __len__ and __getitem__</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">TabularDataset</span>(Dataset):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, X, y):\n        self.X = torch.tensor(X.values, dtype=torch.float32)\n        self.y = torch.tensor(y.values, dtype=torch.long)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__len__</span>(self):\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> len(self.X)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__getitem__</span>(self, idx):\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.X[idx], self.y[idx]   <span class=\"c\"># returns one (input, label) pair</span>\n\ntrain_ds = TabularDataset(X_train, y_train)\nval_ds   = TabularDataset(X_val,   y_val)\n\ntrain_loader = DataLoader(\n    train_ds,\n    batch_size=<span class=\"y\">64</span>,\n    shuffle=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,        <span class=\"c\"># shuffle every epoch during training</span>\n    num_workers=<span class=\"y\">4</span>,       <span class=\"c\"># parallel data loading \u2014 match to CPU cores</span>\n    pin_memory=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># faster CPU\u2192GPU transfer when using CUDA</span>\n    drop_last=<span class=\"y\">True</span>       <span class=\"c\"># drop incomplete final batch (avoids BatchNorm issues)</span>\n)\nval_loader = DataLoader(val_ds, batch_size=<span class=\"y\">128</span>, shuffle=<span class=\"y\">False</span>, num_workers=<span class=\"y\">4</span>)</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 num_workers on Windows and interactive environments</span>\n  <p>num_workers > 0 uses multiprocessing. On Windows this requires the if __name__ == '__main__': guard or it spawns infinite processes. In Jupyter notebooks, num_workers > 0 often causes deadlocks or hangs \u2014 use num_workers=0 (single-process) in notebooks. In production Linux training: set num_workers = number of CPU cores, use pin_memory=True with CUDA.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. TRAINING LOOP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-training\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>The Complete Training Loop</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the canonical PyTorch training pattern</span>\n  <p>Every PyTorch training loop follows the same structure. Deviating from this order causes subtle, hard-to-debug errors. The order is: zero gradients \u2192 forward pass \u2192 compute loss \u2192 backward pass \u2192 (clip gradients) \u2192 optimizer step \u2192 (scheduler step). Understanding why each step is in this position is the difference between using PyTorch and understanding it.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">train_epoch</span>(model, loader, loss_fn, optimizer, device):\n    model.train()   <span class=\"c\"># activates dropout, uses batch stats for BatchNorm</span>\n    total_loss = <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> batch_idx, (x, y) <span class=\"k\">in</span> enumerate(loader):\n        x, y = x.to(device), y.to(device)   <span class=\"c\"># move to GPU</span>\n\n        optimizer.zero_grad()   <span class=\"c\"># 1. clear previous gradients</span>\n        pred = model(x)         <span class=\"c\"># 2. forward pass \u2014 builds computation graph</span>\n        loss = loss_fn(pred, y) <span class=\"c\"># 3. compute loss</span>\n        loss.backward()         <span class=\"c\"># 4. backprop \u2014 fills .grad for all parameters</span>\n        torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># 5. optional</span>\n        optimizer.step()        <span class=\"c\"># 6. update weights using .grad</span>\n        total_loss += loss.item()\n\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> total_loss / len(loader)\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">eval_epoch</span>(model, loader, loss_fn, device):\n    model.eval()    <span class=\"c\"># disables dropout, uses running stats for BatchNorm</span>\n    total_loss, correct = <span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> torch.no_grad():   <span class=\"c\"># disables graph building \u2014 saves memory, faster</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">for</span> x, y <span class=\"k\">in</span> loader:\n            x, y = x.to(device), y.to(device)\n            pred = model(x)\n            total_loss += loss_fn(pred, y).item()\n            correct += (pred.argmax(dim=<span class=\"y\">1</span>) == y).sum().item()\n\n    n = len(loader.dataset)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> total_loss / len(loader), correct / n\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Full training loop</span>\nNUM_EPOCHS = <span class=\"y\">50</span>\nbest_val_loss = float(<span class=\"g\">'inf'</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> epoch <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(NUM_EPOCHS):\n    train_loss = train_epoch(model, train_loader, loss_fn, optimizer, device)\n    val_loss, val_acc = eval_epoch(model, val_loader, loss_fn, device)\n    scheduler.step(val_loss)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> val_loss < best_val_loss:\n        best_val_loss = val_loss\n        torch.save(model.state_dict(), <span class=\"g\">\"best_model.pt\"</span>)\n\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Epoch {epoch+1}: train={train_loss:.4f} val={val_loss:.4f} acc={val_acc:.3f}\"</span>)</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. GPU \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-gpu\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>GPU Training &amp; Mixed Precision</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 GPU training is 10\u2013100\u00d7 faster for matrix operations</span>\n  <p>Neural network training is dominated by matrix multiplications (linear layers, convolutions). GPUs have thousands of small cores designed for parallel floating-point arithmetic \u2014 exactly this operation. A batch of matrix multiplications that takes 10 seconds on CPU takes 0.1 seconds on a modern GPU. For anything beyond small experiments, GPU training is not optional.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 Mixed Precision Training (AMP)</span>\n  <p>Standard training uses float32 (32-bit floats). Mixed precision uses float16 (16-bit) for most operations \u2014 halving memory usage and roughly doubling throughput on modern GPUs (Tensor Cores on NVIDIA V100/A100). A GradScaler handles the instability of float16 gradients (they underflow to zero at small magnitudes) by scaling the loss up before backward, then unscaling before the optimizer step.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> torch.cuda.amp <span class=\"k\">import</span> autocast, GradScaler\n\ndevice = torch.device(<span class=\"g\">\"cuda\"</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> torch.cuda.is_available() <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"g\">\"cpu\"</span>)\nscaler = GradScaler()   <span class=\"c\"># handles float16 gradient scaling</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> x, y <span class=\"k\">in</span> train_loader:\n    x, y = x.to(device), y.to(device)\n    optimizer.zero_grad()\n\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> autocast():          <span class=\"c\"># float16 forward pass \u2014 2\u00d7 faster, 2\u00d7 less memory</span>\n        pred = model(x)\n        loss = loss_fn(pred, y)\n\n    scaler.scale(loss).backward()           <span class=\"c\"># scale loss before backward</span>\n    scaler.unscale_(optimizer)              <span class=\"c\"># unscale gradients before clipping</span>\n    torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), <span class=\"y\">1.0</span>)\n    scaler.step(optimizer)                  <span class=\"c\"># update weights</span>\n    scaler.update()                         <span class=\"c\"># adjust scale factor for next step</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># GPU diagnostics</span>\nprint(torch.cuda.memory_allocated() / <span class=\"y\">1e9</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"GB allocated\"</span>)\nprint(torch.cuda.memory_reserved() / <span class=\"y\">1e9</span>,  <span class=\"g\">\"GB reserved\"</span>)\ntorch.cuda.empty_cache()    <span class=\"c\"># release cached but unused memory</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 CUDA out of memory: the debugging process</span>\n  <p>OOM is the most common GPU error. Debug in this order:<br>\n  1. Reduce batch_size by half. Does it fit? Batch size is the largest lever.<br>\n  2. Enable mixed precision (AMP). Halves activation memory.<br>\n  3. Use gradient checkpointing: <code>torch.utils.checkpoint.checkpoint()</code> \u2014 recomputes activations during backward instead of storing them. Trades compute for memory.<br>\n  4. Use torch.no_grad() for validation \u2014 you're building computation graphs unnecessarily if this is missing.<br>\n  5. Check for tensor accumulation in loops: <code>total_loss += loss</code> (wrong \u2014 keeps graph) vs <code>total_loss += loss.item()</code> (right \u2014 extracts scalar).</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 07. TRANSFER LEARNING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-transfer\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Transfer Learning</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 training from scratch is rarely the right answer</span>\n  <p>Large pretrained models (ResNet, BERT, GPT) have already learned general representations from millions of examples. For most tasks you have hundreds to tens of thousands of examples \u2014 not enough to train such a model from scratch. Transfer learning: start from pretrained weights, adapt to your specific task. You get the benefit of large-scale pretraining with a fraction of the data and compute.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 freeze then fine-tune</span>\n  <p>Two strategies:<br>\n  <strong>Feature extraction:</strong> freeze all pretrained layers (requires_grad=False). Only train a new classification head. Fast, low compute, good when your data is similar to the pretraining data and you have very little of it.<br>\n  <strong>Fine-tuning:</strong> start with pretrained weights, train the whole network (or unfreeze progressively from top to bottom) with a very low learning rate. Better accuracy when you have enough data. Risk: too high a learning rate destroys the pretrained representations (catastrophic forgetting).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> torchvision <span class=\"k\">import</span> models\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Load pretrained model</span>\nmodel = models.resnet50(weights=models.ResNet50_Weights.IMAGENET1K_V2)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Strategy 1: Feature extraction \u2014 freeze everything</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> param <span class=\"k\">in</span> model.parameters():\n    param.requires_grad = <span class=\"y\">False</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Replace the final classification head</span>\nnum_features = model.fc.in_features\nmodel.fc = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(num_features, <span class=\"y\">256</span>),\n    nn.ReLU(),\n    nn.Dropout(<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>),\n    nn.Linear(<span class=\"y\">256</span>, num_classes)    <span class=\"c\"># new head \u2014 requires_grad=True by default</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Only head parameters are trained</span>\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.fc.parameters(), lr=<span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Strategy 2: Progressive unfreezing \u2014 better accuracy</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Phase 1: train head only (5 epochs)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Phase 2: unfreeze last block + head, low LR for pretrained layers</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> param <span class=\"k\">in</span> model.layer4.parameters():\n    param.requires_grad = <span class=\"y\">True</span>\n\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam([\n    {<span class=\"g\">'params'</span>: model.layer4.parameters(), <span class=\"g\">'lr'</span>: <span class=\"y\">1e-5</span>},   <span class=\"c\"># low LR for pretrained</span>\n    {<span class=\"g\">'params'</span>: model.fc.parameters(),     <span class=\"g\">'lr'</span>: <span class=\"y\">1e-3</span>},   <span class=\"c\"># high LR for new head</span>\n])</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 08. CHECKPOINTING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-checkpoint\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Saving &amp; Loading Models</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 state_dict is the right thing to save</span>\n  <p>PyTorch offers two ways to save: save the whole model object (<code>torch.save(model, path)</code>) or save just the state_dict (<code>torch.save(model.state_dict(), path)</code>). Always save the state_dict. Saving the whole model object pickles the class definition \u2014 it breaks whenever you refactor the class, rename files, or load in a different environment. The state_dict is just a dictionary of {parameter_name: tensor} \u2014 portable, stable, and small.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Saving \u2014 save state dict, not the model object</span>\ntorch.save(model.state_dict(), <span class=\"g\">\"model_weights.pt\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Loading</span>\nmodel = MLPClassifier(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">784</span>, hidden_dim=<span class=\"y\">256</span>, num_classes=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\nmodel.load_state_dict(torch.load(<span class=\"g\">\"model_weights.pt\"</span>, map_location=device))\nmodel.eval()   <span class=\"c\"># always set eval mode after loading for inference</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Full checkpoint \u2014 saves everything needed to resume training</span>\ncheckpoint = {\n    <span class=\"g\">'epoch'</span>:      epoch,\n    <span class=\"g\">'model'</span>:      model.state_dict(),\n    <span class=\"g\">'optimizer'</span>:  optimizer.state_dict(),\n    <span class=\"g\">'scheduler'</span>:  scheduler.state_dict(),\n    <span class=\"g\">'val_loss'</span>:   best_val_loss,\n}\ntorch.save(checkpoint, <span class=\"g\">\"checkpoint.pt\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Resuming training from checkpoint</span>\nckpt = torch.load(<span class=\"g\">\"checkpoint.pt\"</span>, map_location=device)\nmodel.load_state_dict(ckpt[<span class=\"g\">'model'</span>])\noptimizer.load_state_dict(ckpt[<span class=\"g\">'optimizer'</span>])\nscheduler.load_state_dict(ckpt[<span class=\"g\">'scheduler'</span>])\nstart_epoch = ckpt[<span class=\"g\">'epoch'</span>] + <span class=\"y\">1</span></div>\n\n<!-- Q&A -->\n<h2 id=\"pt-qa\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n<div class=\"qa-head\">\n  <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n  <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n</div>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between model.train() and model.eval()?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">model.train() activates dropout (randomly zeroes neurons) and makes BatchNorm use mini-batch statistics (mean/variance computed on the current batch). model.eval() disables dropout (all neurons active, outputs scaled by 1\u2212p) and makes BatchNorm use running statistics accumulated during training instead of current batch statistics. Forgetting model.eval() during validation causes two bugs simultaneously: dropout introduces random variation making metrics non-reproducible, and BatchNorm uses noisy batch statistics instead of stable running estimates causing accuracy drops. Always pair model.eval() with torch.no_grad() for inference \u2014 no_grad() stops the computation graph from being built, saving memory and compute.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why do you call optimizer.zero_grad() before loss.backward()?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">PyTorch accumulates gradients in the .grad attribute \u2014 each call to backward() adds to whatever is already there rather than replacing it. This is intentional for gradient accumulation (simulating larger batch sizes across multiple forward-backward passes). But for normal training, you want fresh gradients every step. If you forget zero_grad(), the gradient for step 2 includes the gradient from step 1, producing wrong updates that compound over training. zero_grad() must come before backward(), not after step() \u2014 some engineers call it after step(), which works but is confusing because the gradients are stale for inspection purposes.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between saving model.state_dict() vs saving the whole model?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Saving the whole model (torch.save(model, path)) pickles the Python object including its class definition. Loading it requires the exact same class definition to be importable from the same module path. If you refactor the code, rename files, or load in a different environment, it fails. Saving state_dict saves only the parameter tensors as a plain dictionary \u2014 no class dependency. To load: instantiate the model class normally, then call load_state_dict(). This is portable across code refactors, deployments, and environments. Always save state_dict for anything that needs to survive beyond the current script.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "dl_cnns": "<main>\n<h1>CNNs \u2014 Convolutional Neural Networks</h1>\n\n<div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n  <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n  <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-why\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Why CNNs exist</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why MLPs fail on images \u2014 the pixel problem</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-conv\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Convolution operation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Kernels, feature maps, how sliding works</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-params\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Padding, stride, pooling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Spatial size control, translation invariance</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-arch\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Architecture patterns</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">LeNet \u2192 VGG \u2192 ResNet \u2014 what each solved</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-resnet\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">ResNet and skip connections</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The problem with very deep networks \u2014 and the fix</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"cnn-transfer\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Transfer learning with CNNs</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">When to freeze, when to fine-tune, which model</span></div></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Why CNNs:</strong> a 224\u00d7224 RGB image has 150,528 pixels. An MLP with one hidden layer of 1000 neurons needs 150M parameters for just the first layer. CNNs use weight sharing \u2014 the same small filter slides across the image, learning one feature (edge, curve) everywhere simultaneously. This reduces parameters by 1000\u00d7 while being more effective because natural images have translation invariance: a cat in the top-left and a cat in the bottom-right are the same cat.</li>\n    <li><strong>Convolution:</strong> a small weight matrix (kernel) slides across the input, computing a dot product at each position. Output value = \u03a3(kernel \u00d7 local_input_patch) + bias. One kernel produces one feature map. 64 kernels produce 64 feature maps \u2014 each detecting a different pattern.</li>\n    <li><strong>Output size formula:</strong> ((W \u2212 K + 2P) / S) + 1, where W=input size, K=kernel size, P=padding, S=stride. Input 28\u00d728, kernel 3\u00d73, padding 1, stride 1 \u2192 output 28\u00d728 (same padding preserves spatial size).</li>\n    <li><strong>Max pooling:</strong> divides feature map into non-overlapping windows, takes maximum. 2\u00d72 pooling halves spatial dimensions. Reduces parameters, provides translation invariance within the pooling window, discards exact position of features.</li>\n    <li><strong>ResNet skip connections:</strong> output = F(x) + x. The layer learns the residual (difference from identity) instead of the full transformation. Gradient highway: gradients flow directly through the addition operation with gradient 1 \u2014 no vanishing. Enabled training of 100\u20131000 layer networks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transfer learning choice:</strong> ImageNet-pretrained ResNet50 or EfficientNet as backbone. Freeze all layers \u2192 add new head \u2192 train head only \u2192 gradually unfreeze from top. Use a very low LR (1e-5) for pretrained layers to avoid catastrophic forgetting.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 01. WHY \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-why\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Why CNNs \u2014 The Problem With MLPs on Images</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 MLPs are the wrong tool for images</span>\n  <p>A 224\u00d7224 RGB image has 224 \u00d7 224 \u00d7 3 = 150,528 input values. An MLP with a first hidden layer of 1,000 neurons needs 150,528 \u00d7 1,000 = 150 million parameters in the first layer alone. Three critical problems:<br><br>\n  <strong>1. Scale:</strong> the parameter count is intractable. AlexNet would need 25 billion parameters as an MLP.<br>\n  <strong>2. Spatial blindness:</strong> an MLP treats pixel (0,0) and pixel (223,223) as equally related to each other as pixel (0,0) and pixel (0,1). Spatial structure is completely ignored \u2014 there's no concept of neighbouring pixels.<br>\n  <strong>3. No translation invariance:</strong> an MLP learns that a cat in position (50,50) is a cat. It has no mechanism to recognise the same cat in position (100,100) without seeing that exact position in training data.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the two key ideas CNNs introduce</span>\n  <p><strong>Weight sharing:</strong> the same small filter (e.g. 3\u00d73 kernel) is applied at every spatial position of the image. All positions share the same 9 weights. One filter that detects horizontal edges detects them everywhere \u2014 top-left, bottom-right, centre \u2014 with the same 9 parameters.<br><br>\n  <strong>Local connectivity:</strong> each output value only depends on a small local patch of the input (the receptive field). Nearby pixels are more related than distant ones \u2014 this structural assumption is baked into the architecture and is correct for natural images.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 02. CONVOLUTION \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-conv\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>The Convolution Operation</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 how convolution computes a feature map</span>\n  <p>A kernel (filter) is a small weight matrix, e.g. 3\u00d73. It slides across the input image with a defined step (stride). At each position, it computes the dot product between the kernel weights and the local input patch under it, adds a bias, and writes the result to the output (feature map).<br><br>\n  <strong>Output value at position (i,j) = \u03a3\u2099 \u03a3\u2098 kernel[n,m] \u00d7 input[i+n, j+m] + bias</strong><br><br>\n  One kernel \u2192 one feature map (one channel of output). 64 kernels \u2192 64 feature maps. Each kernel learns to detect a different pattern: one detects horizontal edges, another detects diagonal lines, another detects a specific texture.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 a spotlight scanning a stage</span>\n  <p>A theatre spotlight (the kernel) shines a 3\u00d73 area. It moves systematically across the stage (the image), illuminating each patch. At each position it answers one question: \"how much does this patch look like what I'm detecting?\" The answer (a single number) is recorded on a map \u2014 bright where the pattern was found, dark where it wasn't. That map is the feature map.<br><br>\n  64 different spotlights running simultaneously, each asking a different question, produce 64 different maps \u2014 the 64 channels of the convolutional layer's output.</p>\n</div>\n\n<figure>\n  <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 195\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">Convolution: 3\u00d73 kernel sliding across input \u2192 feature map</text>\n    <!-- Input grid -->\n    <text x=\"100\" y=\"42\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Input (5\u00d75)</text>\n    <g stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1\" fill=\"var(--s1)\">\n      <rect x=\"25\" y=\"50\" width=\"150\" height=\"130\" rx=\"4\"/>\n      <line x1=\"55\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"55\" y2=\"180\"/><line x1=\"85\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"85\" y2=\"180\"/>\n      <line x1=\"115\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"115\" y2=\"180\"/><line x1=\"145\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"145\" y2=\"180\"/>\n      <line x1=\"25\" y1=\"76\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"76\"/><line x1=\"25\" y1=\"102\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"102\"/>\n      <line x1=\"25\" y1=\"128\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"128\"/><line x1=\"25\" y1=\"154\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"154\"/>\n    </g>\n    <rect x=\"25\" y=\"50\" width=\"90\" height=\"78\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"var(--blue-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--blue)\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n    <text x=\"70\" y=\"44\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"var(--blue)\" font-weight=\"700\">receptive field</text>\n    <!-- Kernel -->\n    <text x=\"310\" y=\"42\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Kernel (3\u00d73)</text>\n    <g stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"var(--violet-dim)\">\n      <rect x=\"232\" y=\"50\" width=\"156\" height=\"130\" rx=\"4\"/>\n      <line x1=\"284\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"284\" y2=\"180\"/><line x1=\"336\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"336\" y2=\"180\"/>\n      <line x1=\"232\" y1=\"93\" x2=\"388\" y2=\"93\"/><line x1=\"232\" y1=\"136\" x2=\"388\" y2=\"136\"/>\n    </g>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">1</text>\n    <text x=\"310\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">0</text>\n    <text x=\"362\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">-1</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">2</text>\n    <text x=\"310\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">0</text>\n    <text x=\"362\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">-2</text>\n    <text x=\"258\" y=\"163\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">1</text>\n    <text x=\"310\" y=\"163\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">0</text>\n    <text x=\"362\" y=\"163\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">-1</text>\n    <text x=\"310\" y=\"193\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">Sobel vertical edge detector</text>\n    <!-- Arrow -->\n    <text x=\"430\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"22\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">\u2192</text>\n    <!-- Output -->\n    <text x=\"580\" y=\"42\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Feature map (3\u00d73)</text>\n    <g stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\">\n      <rect x=\"458\" y=\"50\" width=\"244\" height=\"130\" rx=\"4\"/>\n      <line x1=\"539\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"539\" y2=\"180\"/><line x1=\"620\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"620\" y2=\"180\"/>\n      <line x1=\"458\" y1=\"93\" x2=\"702\" y2=\"93\"/><line x1=\"458\" y1=\"136\" x2=\"702\" y2=\"136\"/>\n    </g>\n    <text x=\"499\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"var(--green)\" font-weight=\"600\">high</text>\n    <text x=\"580\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"var(--green)\" font-weight=\"600\">low</text>\n    <text x=\"661\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"var(--red)\">neg</text>\n    <text x=\"499\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">vertical</text>\n    <text x=\"499\" y=\"133\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">edge here</text>\n    <text x=\"580\" y=\"193\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"var(--green)\">bright = strong vertical edge detected</text>\n  </svg>\n</figure>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 confusing channels with feature maps</span>\n  <p>Input image: 3 channels (RGB). After a conv layer with 64 kernels: 64 channels (64 feature maps). Each of the 64 kernels operates across all 3 input channels simultaneously \u2014 a 3\u00d73\u00d73 kernel, not a 3\u00d73 kernel. The kernel has depth equal to the number of input channels. Output has depth equal to the number of kernels. A Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3) layer has 64 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 3 + 64 = 1,792 parameters (64 kernels \u00d7 3 input channels \u00d7 3\u00d73 spatial \u00d7 plus 64 biases).</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 03. PARAMS \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-params\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Padding, Stride, and Pooling</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the spatial size formula</span>\n  <p>Output spatial size = \u230a(W \u2212 K + 2P) / S\u230b + 1<br>\n  W = input size, K = kernel size, P = padding (zeros added to border), S = stride (step size).<br><br>\n  <strong>Padding=1, K=3, S=1:</strong> (W \u2212 3 + 2) / 1 + 1 = W. Same padding \u2014 output same size as input. Standard in modern CNNs to preserve spatial size through conv layers.<br>\n  <strong>S=2:</strong> output is half the input size. Used to downsample instead of pooling.<br>\n  <strong>K=1, P=0, S=1:</strong> 1\u00d71 convolution \u2014 output same spatial size, but changes channel depth. Used for channel mixing without spatial computation (cheap, powerful).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 max pooling</span>\n  <p>Divides the feature map into non-overlapping windows (e.g. 2\u00d72) and takes the maximum value in each window. 2\u00d72 max pooling halves the spatial dimensions \u2014 32\u00d732 feature map \u2192 16\u00d716. Reduces parameter count in subsequent layers, provides local translation invariance (a feature detected 1 pixel to the left still produces the same pooling output), and builds position robustness into the network.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 modern networks prefer strided conv over max pooling</span>\n  <p>Max pooling discards information \u2014 it only keeps the maximum, throwing away where the maximum was and what the other values were. Strided convolutions (S=2) downsample while still learning what to keep \u2014 the weights are trained, not fixed. ResNet uses strided conv for downsampling. The trend: pooling is being replaced by learned downsampling. Average pooling persists in the final global average pooling layer before the classifier head.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 04. ARCHITECTURES \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-arch\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Architecture Evolution</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY the history matters \u2014 each architecture solved a specific failure</span>\n  <p>Understanding what problem each architecture solved is more valuable than memorising layer counts. Interviewers ask \"why skip connections?\" not \"how many layers does ResNet-50 have?\"</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW each generation solved the previous generation's problem</span>\n  <p><strong>LeNet (1989):</strong> proved CNNs work for digit recognition. 2 conv layers, small by modern standards. Problem: too shallow for complex tasks.<br><br>\n  <strong>AlexNet (2012):</strong> deep enough to win ImageNet by a 10% margin. Key innovations: ReLU instead of tanh (solved vanishing gradient), dropout (regularisation), GPU training (made depth feasible). Proved deep learning scales. Problem: very large fully-connected layers (60M params, mostly in FC layers).<br><br>\n  <strong>VGGNet (2014):</strong> showed that depth matters \u2014 stack many 3\u00d73 convolutions instead of one large 11\u00d711. Two 3\u00d73 convolutions have the same receptive field as one 5\u00d75 but fewer parameters and an extra non-linearity. Problem: very memory-hungry, still large FC layers.<br><br>\n  <strong>ResNet (2015):</strong> solved degradation \u2014 deeper networks were performing worse, not better, despite having more capacity. Skip connections fix this. 152 layers became trainable. Problem: still compute-heavy.<br><br>\n  <strong>EfficientNet (2019):</strong> showed that scaling width, depth, and resolution together (compound scaling) produces better accuracy/compute trade-offs than scaling any one dimension alone. EfficientNet-B0 achieves ResNet-50 accuracy with 5\u00d7 fewer parameters.</p>\n</div>\n\n<table class=\"tbl\">\n  <tr><th>Architecture</th><th>Year</th><th>Key innovation</th><th>ImageNet top-5</th><th>Params</th></tr>\n  <tr><td>AlexNet</td><td>2012</td><td>Deep CNN on GPU, ReLU, dropout</td><td>84.7%</td><td>60M</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>VGGNet-16</td><td>2014</td><td>Depth via small 3\u00d73 kernels only</td><td>92.7%</td><td>138M</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>ResNet-50</td><td>2015</td><td>Skip connections, batch norm</td><td>93.3%</td><td>25M</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>EfficientNet-B4</td><td>2019</td><td>Compound scaling</td><td>97.0%</td><td>19M</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 05. RESNET \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-resnet\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>ResNet and Skip Connections</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 very deep networks degrade without skip connections</span>\n  <p>In 2015, adding more layers to a CNN was making it worse, not better \u2014 and this wasn't overfitting (training loss also increased). The degradation problem: very deep networks were harder to optimise, not just harder to generalise. Gradients were too weak to update early layers, and the network couldn't even learn an identity mapping (copy input to output) through many layers when that was the optimal solution.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the residual learning framework</span>\n  <p>Instead of learning H(x) (the full desired mapping), let the layers learn the residual F(x) = H(x) \u2212 x. The block output is:<br><br>\n  <strong>output = F(x) + x</strong><br><br>\n  F(x) is what the conv layers compute. x is the original input, added directly via a shortcut connection (skip connection) that bypasses the conv layers. If the optimal function is the identity (copy input), the layers just need to learn F(x) = 0 \u2014 which is easy. If they need to learn a transformation, they learn the difference from identity \u2014 which is easier than learning the full transformation from scratch.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW skip connections fix the vanishing gradient</span>\n  <p>During backprop, the gradient flows through the addition operation: \u2202L/\u2202x = \u2202L/\u2202output \u00d7 (\u2202F(x)/\u2202x + 1). The +1 term means the gradient always has a direct path back through the skip connection with gradient 1, regardless of what the conv layers are doing. Even if the conv layers have tiny gradients, the skip connection carries a full gradient signal back to early layers. This is the gradient highway \u2014 why ResNets can be 100\u20131000 layers deep and still train.</p>\n</div>\n\n<figure>\n  <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 170\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">ResNet residual block \u2014 skip connection is the gradient highway</text>\n    <!-- Without skip -->\n    <rect x=\"12\" y=\"28\" width=\"310\" height=\"130\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--red)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Plain network \u2014 gradient struggles</text>\n    <rect x=\"60\" y=\"60\" width=\"70\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--s2)\" stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"95\" y=\"79\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Conv + BN + ReLU</text>\n    <path d=\"M130 75 L160 75\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#ca1)\"/>\n    <rect x=\"160\" y=\"60\" width=\"70\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--s2)\" stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"195\" y=\"79\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Conv + BN + ReLU</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Gradient shrinks at each layer</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"136\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Early layers starved of signal</text>\n    <text x=\"167\" y=\"152\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Degradation with depth</text>\n    <!-- With skip -->\n    <rect x=\"378\" y=\"28\" width=\"310\" height=\"130\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">ResNet block \u2014 skip connection</text>\n    <rect x=\"420\" y=\"60\" width=\"70\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--s2)\" stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"455\" y=\"79\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Conv + BN + ReLU</text>\n    <path d=\"M490 75 L520 75\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#ca1)\"/>\n    <rect x=\"520\" y=\"60\" width=\"70\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--s2)\" stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n    <text x=\"555\" y=\"79\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Conv + BN</text>\n    <path d=\"M590 75 L625 75\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#ca1)\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"635\" cy=\"75\" r=\"12\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n    <text x=\"635\" y=\"79\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" fill=\"var(--green)\" font-weight=\"700\">+</text>\n    <path d=\"M405 75 Q405 40 635 40 L635 63\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" stroke-dasharray=\"5 3\" marker-end=\"url(#ca2)\"/>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">output = F(x) + x</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"136\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Gradient: \u2202L/\u2202x = grad \u00d7 (\u2202F/\u2202x + 1)</text>\n    <text x=\"533\" y=\"152\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">+1 = highway for gradient flow \u2713</text>\n    <defs>\n      <marker id=\"ca1\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\"/></marker>\n      <marker id=\"ca2\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"var(--green)\"/></marker>\n    </defs>\n  </svg>\n</figure>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 06. TRANSFER LEARNING \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-transfer\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Transfer Learning with CNNs</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 which layers to freeze and which to train</span>\n  <p>Pretrained CNNs learn a feature hierarchy: early layers detect edges and textures (universal to all images); late layers detect task-specific objects. How much to freeze depends on how similar your task is to ImageNet and how much labelled data you have:<br><br>\n  <strong>Very little data (&lt;1K examples), task similar to ImageNet:</strong> freeze all conv layers, train only the new head. The pretrained features are good enough; retraining would overfit.<br>\n  <strong>Moderate data (1K\u2013100K), task similar:</strong> freeze early layers (layers 1\u20133 of ResNet), fine-tune late layers + new head with a low LR (1e-4 to 1e-5).<br>\n  <strong>Large data or very different task:</strong> fine-tune the whole network. Still initialise from pretrained weights \u2014 they're a better starting point than random init even for different domains.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 catastrophic forgetting from too high a learning rate</span>\n  <p>Fine-tuning a pretrained ResNet with LR=1e-3 on the pretrained layers destroys the learned representations within a few epochs. The new task's gradients overwrite years of ImageNet pretraining. Symptom: fine-tuned model performs worse than just using frozen features. Fix: differential learning rates \u2014 the new head gets a high LR (1e-3), pretrained layers get a 10\u2013100\u00d7 lower LR (1e-5 to 1e-4). PyTorch optimizer supports this via parameter groups.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- Q&A -->\n<h2 id=\"cnn-qa\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n<div class=\"qa-head\">\n  <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n  <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n</div>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why do we use CNNs for images instead of MLPs?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Three reasons. (1) Parameter efficiency: a 224\u00d7224\u00d73 image has 150K pixels. An MLP first layer of 1000 neurons needs 150M parameters. A CNN uses weight sharing \u2014 the same 3\u00d73 kernel slides across the image, learning one pattern everywhere with 9 parameters. (2) Spatial structure: an MLP has no concept of neighbouring pixels \u2014 it treats every pixel pair as equally related. CNNs exploit local connectivity: each output depends only on a nearby input patch. (3) Translation invariance: a cat in the top-left and a cat in the bottom-right use the same kernel weights. An MLP would need separate weights for every possible position. CNNs learn position-invariant features by design.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What problem do ResNet's skip connections solve and how?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The degradation problem: adding more layers was making networks perform worse even on training data \u2014 not overfitting, but failure to optimise. Very deep networks couldn't learn even simple identity mappings through many layers. Skip connections: output = F(x) + x, where F(x) is what the conv layers compute and x is the input passed directly via a shortcut. Two benefits: (1) Easier optimisation \u2014 if the optimal function is identity, the layers just learn F(x) = 0, which is trivial. Learning the full transformation H(x) = x is surprisingly hard for deep networks. (2) Gradient highway \u2014 during backprop, gradient flows directly through the addition with gradient 1, regardless of what the conv layers do. This ensures even 100+ layer early layers receive gradient signal. ResNet enabled 152-layer networks where plain nets failed at 20.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>You have 500 labelled images of a medical scan type. How do you build a classifier?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">500 images is far too little to train a CNN from scratch \u2014 random init would overfit immediately. Transfer learning: load a ResNet50 or EfficientNet pretrained on ImageNet. Freeze all convolutional layers. Replace the final classification head with a new Linear layer (512 \u2192 num_classes) with dropout. Train only the new head for 20\u201330 epochs with LR=1e-3. This uses ImageNet's learned edge/texture/shape representations \u2014 which transfer well to medical images despite domain difference. If accuracy plateaus: gradually unfreeze the last ResNet block, train with LR=1e-5 for pretrained layers and 1e-4 for new head. Data augmentation is critical with small datasets: random horizontal flip, rotation \u00b115\u00b0, colour jitter, random crop \u2014 this effectively multiplies your training set size.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "dl_rnns": "<main>\n<h1>RNNs &amp; Sequential Models</h1>\n\n<div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n  <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n  <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-why\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Why sequential models</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">MLPs and CNNs cannot handle variable-length sequences</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-arch\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">RNN architecture</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Hidden state, the recurrence equation, unrolling</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-vanish\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Vanishing gradient in RNNs</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why RNNs forget \u2014 the mathematical reason</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-lstm\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">LSTM</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Cell state, gates, how long-term memory works</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-gru\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">GRU</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Simpler than LSTM \u2014 when it's enough</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"rnn-variants\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Variants &amp; practical use</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Bidirectional, seq2seq, when to use RNNs vs Transformers</span></div></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Why RNNs:</strong> a sentence \"The cat sat on the mat\" has variable length and word order matters. An MLP needs fixed-size input and treats each input element independently \u2014 no order awareness. CNNs detect local patterns but don't model long-range dependencies across a sequence. RNNs process sequences one element at a time, maintaining a hidden state that carries information from previous steps.</li>\n    <li><strong>RNN equation:</strong> h\u209c = tanh(W\u2095\u2095h\u209c\u208b\u2081 + W\u2093\u2095x\u209c + b). Hidden state h\u209c depends on previous hidden state h\u209c\u208b\u2081 and current input x\u209c. Same weight matrices W\u2095\u2095 and W\u2093\u2095 used at every timestep \u2014 weight sharing across time. Output at each step: y\u209c = W\u2095\u1d67h\u209c.</li>\n    <li><strong>Vanishing gradient:</strong> BPTT multiplies gradients across timesteps. At step T, the gradient for step 1 involves a product of T Jacobian matrices. If the spectral radius of W\u2095\u2095 &lt; 1, this product shrinks exponentially \u2014 step 1 receives zero gradient, no learning from long-range dependencies. If &gt; 1, explodes (fix with gradient clipping).</li>\n    <li><strong>LSTM cell state:</strong> a separate \"conveyor belt\" that runs alongside the hidden state. Gates control what enters (input gate), what's forgotten (forget gate), and what exits to the hidden state (output gate). The cell state can carry information across hundreds of timesteps with minimal degradation because the gradient path through the cell state is addition, not multiplication.</li>\n    <li><strong>GRU:</strong> merges cell state and hidden state into one. Two gates (reset and update) instead of LSTM's three. Fewer parameters, slightly faster, competitive performance. Prefer GRU when: smaller datasets, computational budget is tight, empirical performance matches LSTM.</li>\n    <li><strong>Bidirectional RNN:</strong> two RNNs \u2014 one processes left-to-right, one right-to-left. Concatenate hidden states at each timestep. Useful when the full sequence is available (not real-time generation). Standard for sequence labelling tasks (NER, POS tagging).</li>\n    <li><strong>RNN vs Transformer:</strong> Transformers have replaced RNNs for almost all NLP tasks because: they process the full sequence in parallel (no sequential bottleneck), self-attention directly connects any two positions (no gradient through many timesteps), and they scale much better with model size and data. RNNs remain relevant for: streaming/online prediction, very long sequences that don't fit in attention memory, embedded systems.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 01. WHY \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-why\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Why Sequential Models</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 fixed-size architectures fail on sequences</span>\n  <p>Language, time series, audio \u2014 all are sequences where: (1) the input length varies from example to example, (2) the order of elements encodes meaning, and (3) context from earlier elements is needed to interpret later ones.<br><br>\n  MLP: requires fixed input size. Flattening a variable-length sentence loses order. No mechanism to share weights across positions.<br>\n  CNN: fixed window sizes capture local patterns but miss long-range dependencies. \"The bank by the river\" vs \"The bank where I deposit money\" \u2014 the disambiguation requires context far outside any fixed window.<br><br>\n  Needed: a model that processes one element at a time, in order, and carries a \"memory\" of what it has seen so far into each next step.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 02. RNN ARCHITECTURE \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-arch\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>RNN Architecture</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the recurrence equation</span>\n  <p>At each timestep t, the RNN receives the current input x\u209c and the previous hidden state h\u209c\u208b\u2081, producing a new hidden state h\u209c:<br><br>\n  <strong>h\u209c = tanh(W\u2093\u2095x\u209c + W\u2095\u2095h\u209c\u208b\u2081 + b)</strong><br><br>\n  The same weight matrices W\u2093\u2095 and W\u2095\u2095 are used at every timestep \u2014 weight sharing across time, analogous to how CNNs share weights across space. h\u2080 is initialised to zeros. The output at each step (if needed) is y\u209c = W\u2095\u1d67h\u209c.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 reading a sentence and building understanding</span>\n  <p>You read \"The cat sat on the...\" word by word. After \"The\" you hold \"article detected, something follows.\" After \"cat\" you update to \"animal, subject identified.\" After \"sat\" you update to \"action taken, past tense.\" Each new word modifies your current understanding \u2014 you don't start from scratch at each word. The hidden state h\u209c is exactly that accumulated understanding at step t.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW \u2014 unrolling through time</span>\n  <p>An RNN with a 5-word input can be \"unrolled\" into 5 copies of the same network arranged in sequence, each receiving the current word and passing its hidden state to the next copy. This unrolled view makes backpropagation clear: gradients flow backwards through each timestep \u2014 called Backpropagation Through Time (BPTT). The key insight: the same weights appear at every timestep in the unrolled graph, so gradients for the weights sum across all timesteps.</p>\n</div>\n\n<figure>\n  <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 170\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">RNN unrolled \u2014 same weights at every step, hidden state carries memory</text>\n    <defs>\n      <marker id=\"rna\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\"/></marker>\n      <marker id=\"rnb\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"var(--blue)\"/></marker>\n    </defs>\n    <!-- Timestep boxes -->\n    <g fill=\"var(--blue-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--blue)\" stroke-width=\"2\">\n      <rect x=\"55\"  y=\"65\" width=\"80\" height=\"50\" rx=\"8\"/>\n      <rect x=\"215\" y=\"65\" width=\"80\" height=\"50\" rx=\"8\"/>\n      <rect x=\"375\" y=\"65\" width=\"80\" height=\"50\" rx=\"8\"/>\n      <rect x=\"535\" y=\"65\" width=\"80\" height=\"50\" rx=\"8\"/>\n    </g>\n    <g text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">\n      <text x=\"95\"  y=\"94\">RNN</text>\n      <text x=\"255\" y=\"94\">RNN</text>\n      <text x=\"415\" y=\"94\">RNN</text>\n      <text x=\"575\" y=\"94\">RNN</text>\n    </g>\n    <!-- Inputs -->\n    <g text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">\n      <text x=\"95\"  y=\"155\">x\u2081 = \"The\"</text>\n      <text x=\"255\" y=\"155\">x\u2082 = \"cat\"</text>\n      <text x=\"415\" y=\"155\">x\u2083 = \"sat\"</text>\n      <text x=\"575\" y=\"155\">x\u2084 = \"on\"</text>\n    </g>\n    <g stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\">\n      <path d=\"M95 145 L95 118\" marker-end=\"url(#rna)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M255 145 L255 118\" marker-end=\"url(#rna)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M415 145 L415 118\" marker-end=\"url(#rna)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M575 145 L575 118\" marker-end=\"url(#rna)\"/>\n    </g>\n    <!-- Hidden state arrows -->\n    <g stroke=\"var(--blue)\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\">\n      <path d=\"M20 90 L55 90\"   marker-end=\"url(#rnb)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M135 90 L215 90\" marker-end=\"url(#rnb)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M295 90 L375 90\" marker-end=\"url(#rnb)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M455 90 L535 90\" marker-end=\"url(#rnb)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M615 90 L650 90\" marker-end=\"url(#rnb)\"/>\n    </g>\n    <g text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">\n      <text x=\"33\"  y=\"82\">h\u2080</text>\n      <text x=\"175\" y=\"82\">h\u2081</text>\n      <text x=\"335\" y=\"82\">h\u2082</text>\n      <text x=\"495\" y=\"82\">h\u2083</text>\n      <text x=\"635\" y=\"82\">h\u2084</text>\n    </g>\n    <text x=\"20\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">zeros</text>\n    <text x=\"350\" y=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Same W\u2093\u2095 and W\u2095\u2095 shared at every timestep (weight tying)</text>\n  </svg>\n</figure>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 03. VANISHING GRADIENT \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-vanish\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>The Vanishing Gradient Problem in RNNs</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY this is RNNs' fundamental failure mode</span>\n  <p>For a sequence of length T, BPTT must propagate gradients through T timesteps. The gradient for the weight at timestep 1 involves a product of T Jacobian matrices \u2014 one per timestep. Specifically, the gradient involves repeated multiplication by \u2202h\u209c/\u2202h\u209c\u208b\u2081 = W\u2095\u2095\u1d40 \u00d7 diag(1 \u2212 h\u209c\u00b2) (the tanh derivative term).<br><br>\n  If the largest eigenvalue (spectral radius) of W\u2095\u2095 &lt; 1: the product shrinks exponentially with T. At T=50, the gradient at step 1 is essentially zero. The network cannot learn dependencies that span more than ~10 timesteps.<br><br>\n  If spectral radius &gt; 1: the product explodes exponentially. Gradients become NaN. Fix for exploding: gradient clipping. But there's no symmetric fix for vanishing \u2014 you need a different architecture.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 a game of telephone across 50 people</span>\n  <p>Whisper a sentence to person 1. They pass it to person 2, who passes to person 3, and so on. By person 50, the original message is unrecognisable \u2014 noise accumulated at each step. This is what happens to gradient signals in a vanilla RNN across 50 timesteps. The gradient (the \"message\" to early layers about how to update) becomes noise before it reaches timestep 1. The network literally cannot learn that word 1 is relevant to the meaning at word 50.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 04. LSTM \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-lstm\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>LSTM \u2014 Long Short-Term Memory</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 a separate memory lane for long-range information</span>\n  <p>LSTM adds a second state vector called the <strong>cell state</strong> c\u209c, which runs alongside the hidden state h\u209c. The key architectural choice: information flows through the cell state via <em>addition</em> rather than multiplication. Addition does not shrink gradients. The cell state is a \"conveyor belt\" \u2014 information placed on it at step 1 can survive to step 100 with its gradient intact.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the three gates</span>\n  <p>Gates are sigmoid-activated neural networks that output values in (0,1) \u2014 acting as soft \"valves\" controlling information flow.<br><br>\n  <strong>Forget gate:</strong> f\u209c = \u03c3(Wf\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c] + bf). Decides what fraction of the previous cell state to keep. f\u209c=1: keep everything. f\u209c=0: forget everything. \"I'm reading a new paragraph, forget the previous subject.\"<br><br>\n  <strong>Input gate + candidate:</strong> i\u209c = \u03c3(Wi\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c] + bi). c\u0303\u209c = tanh(Wc\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c] + bc). i\u209c controls how much of the new candidate c\u0303\u209c to write to cell state. \"There's new subject matter to remember.\"<br><br>\n  <strong>Cell state update:</strong> c\u209c = f\u209c \u2299 c\u209c\u208b\u2081 + i\u209c \u2299 c\u0303\u209c. Forget old, add new.<br><br>\n  <strong>Output gate:</strong> o\u209c = \u03c3(Wo\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c] + bo). h\u209c = o\u209c \u2299 tanh(c\u209c). Decides what to expose from cell state as the current hidden state.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 a notepad with selective read/write/erase</span>\n  <p>The cell state is a notepad. The forget gate decides which notes to erase (multiply by 0\u20131). The input gate decides what new notes to write. The output gate decides which notes to read aloud (contribute to h\u209c). Unlike vanilla RNN which overwrites the entire state at each step, the LSTM surgically updates only what the gates allow \u2014 old information survives unless explicitly erased.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW gradient flow through the cell state avoids vanishing</span>\n  <p>The gradient of the loss w.r.t. c\u209c\u208b\u2081 involves \u2202c\u209c/\u2202c\u209c\u208b\u2081 = f\u209c. This is element-wise multiplication by the forget gate \u2014 not a matrix multiplication involving W\u2095\u2095. The gradient through the cell state is: \u2202L/\u2202c\u2081 = \u2202L/\u2202cT \u00d7 f_T \u00d7 f_{T-1} \u00d7 ... \u00d7 f_2. Each f\u209c is learned independently and can be close to 1 when the network needs to remember. This controlled gradient path is why LSTMs handle sequences of hundreds of steps where RNNs fail at tens.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Single LSTM layer</span>\nlstm = nn.LSTM(\n    input_size=<span class=\"y\">128</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># dimension of each input token embedding</span>\n    hidden_size=<span class=\"y\">256</span>,   <span class=\"c\"># dimension of hidden state and cell state</span>\n    num_layers=<span class=\"y\">2</span>,      <span class=\"c\"># stacked LSTMs \u2014 each layer's h becomes next layer's input</span>\n    batch_first=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,  <span class=\"c\"># input shape: (batch, seq_len, input_size)</span>\n    dropout=<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>,       <span class=\"c\"># dropout BETWEEN stacked layers (not on top layer)</span>\n    bidirectional=<span class=\"y\">False</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># input: (batch, seq_len, input_size)</span>\nx = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">50</span>, <span class=\"y\">128</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># batch=32, seq=50 words, embed=128</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Initial hidden and cell state (zeros by default if not provided)</span>\nh0 = torch.zeros(<span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">256</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># (num_layers, batch, hidden_size)</span>\nc0 = torch.zeros(<span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">256</span>)\n\noutput, (hn, cn) = lstm(x, (h0, c0))\n<span class=\"c\"># output: (batch, seq_len, hidden_size) \u2014 h at every timestep</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># hn: (num_layers, batch, hidden_size) \u2014 final hidden state</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># cn: (num_layers, batch, hidden_size) \u2014 final cell state</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># For classification: use last hidden state</span>\nfinal_h = hn[-<span class=\"y\">1</span>]   <span class=\"c\"># (batch, hidden_size) \u2014 last layer's final hidden state</span>\nlogits = classifier_head(final_h)</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 05. GRU \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-gru\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>GRU \u2014 Gated Recurrent Unit</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 LSTM simplified</span>\n  <p>GRU merges the cell state and hidden state into a single hidden state h\u209c, and uses only two gates instead of LSTM's three:<br><br>\n  <strong>Reset gate:</strong> r\u209c = \u03c3(Wr\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c]). Controls how much of previous hidden state to use when computing new candidate. r\u209c\u22480: ignore previous state (useful for starting fresh on a new topic).<br><br>\n  <strong>Update gate:</strong> z\u209c = \u03c3(Wz\u00b7[h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c]). Controls how much of the old hidden state to keep vs the new candidate. z\u209c\u22481: keep old state (nothing new to remember). z\u209c\u22480: replace with new candidate.<br><br>\n  <strong>Candidate:</strong> h\u0303\u209c = tanh(W\u00b7[r\u209c\u2299h\u209c\u208b\u2081, x\u209c])<br>\n  <strong>Update:</strong> h\u209c = (1\u2212z\u209c)\u2299h\u209c\u208b\u2081 + z\u209c\u2299h\u0303\u209c</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">GRU vs LSTM \u2014 when to pick each</span>\n  <p>GRU has fewer parameters (no cell state, 2 gates vs 3). Trains faster. Often matches LSTM performance on smaller datasets. Choose GRU when: computation budget is tight, dataset is small to medium, you want to try the simpler option first. Choose LSTM when: sequences are very long (&gt;200 steps), you need the explicit cell state for fine-grained memory control, or empirical results show LSTM outperforming GRU on your specific task. In practice: start with GRU, switch to LSTM if performance is insufficient.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 06. VARIANTS \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-variants\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Variants and Practical Guidance</h2>\n\n<h3>Bidirectional RNNs</h3>\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT and WHEN</span>\n  <p>Two RNNs: one processes the sequence left-to-right, one right-to-left. At each timestep, concatenate both hidden states: [h\u2192\u209c, h\u2190\u209c]. Each position has context from both past and future. Critical for tasks where context from both directions matters: Named Entity Recognition (\"Bank of England\" \u2014 \"England\" helps understand \"Bank\"), POS tagging, sentiment analysis. Cannot be used for real-time/streaming tasks where future tokens are unavailable.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>When to use RNNs vs Transformers</h3>\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">The honest answer: Transformers have replaced RNNs for most NLP tasks</span>\n  <p>Transformers outperform RNNs on almost all NLP benchmarks because: (1) self-attention directly connects any two positions in O(1) steps \u2014 no gradient through many timesteps, (2) fully parallel processing \u2014 the whole sequence computes simultaneously, not sequentially, (3) scales much better with data and model size.<br><br>\n  RNNs remain relevant when: (1) streaming/online prediction where tokens arrive one at a time and you must respond immediately without waiting for the full sequence, (2) very long sequences where attention's O(n\u00b2) memory is prohibitive (though recent efficient attention methods are changing this), (3) embedded/edge systems where Transformer inference cost is too high, (4) time series with strong sequential structure and small datasets where the inductive bias of RNNs helps.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> torch.nn <span class=\"k\">as</span> nn\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Bidirectional LSTM</span>\nbilstm = nn.LSTM(\n    input_size=<span class=\"y\">128</span>,\n    hidden_size=<span class=\"y\">128</span>,\n    num_layers=<span class=\"y\">2</span>,\n    batch_first=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,\n    bidirectional=<span class=\"y\">True</span>   <span class=\"c\"># doubles the output hidden size</span>\n)\nx = torch.randn(<span class=\"y\">32</span>, <span class=\"y\">50</span>, <span class=\"y\">128</span>)\noutput, _ = bilstm(x)\n<span class=\"c\"># output: (32, 50, 256) \u2014 128 forward + 128 backward concatenated at each step</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Sequence classification with LSTM</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">LSTMClassifier</span>(nn.Module):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, vocab_size, embed_dim, hidden_dim, num_classes, n_layers=<span class=\"y\">2</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">super</span>().__init__()\n        self.embed = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim, padding_idx=<span class=\"y\">0</span>)\n        self.lstm  = nn.LSTM(embed_dim, hidden_dim, n_layers, batch_first=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,\n                             dropout=<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>, bidirectional=<span class=\"y\">True</span>)\n        self.drop  = nn.Dropout(<span class=\"y\">0.3</span>)\n        self.fc    = nn.Linear(hidden_dim * <span class=\"y\">2</span>, num_classes)   <span class=\"c\"># \u00d72 for bidirectional</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">forward</span>(self, x):\n        emb = self.embed(x)\n        out, (hn, _) = self.lstm(emb)\n        <span class=\"c\"># Concatenate final hidden state from both directions</span>\n        h = torch.cat([hn[-<span class=\"y\">2</span>], hn[-<span class=\"y\">1</span>]], dim=<span class=\"y\">1</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># (batch, hidden\u00d72)</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.fc(self.drop(h))</div>\n\n<!-- Q&A -->\n<h2 id=\"rnn-qa\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n<div class=\"qa-head\">\n  <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n  <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n</div>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does the vanishing gradient problem hit RNNs harder than feedforward networks?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">In feedforward networks, depth is fixed and typically 10\u2013100 layers. In RNNs, the network is \"unrolled\" across timesteps \u2014 a sequence of length 500 creates a 500-layer feedforward graph during BPTT. The gradient for step 1 is a product of 499 Jacobian matrices, each involving W\u2095\u2095\u1d40 \u00d7 diag(tanh'). If the spectral radius of W\u2095\u2095 &lt; 1 (which is common with random init), this product shrinks exponentially. At step 1 the gradient is machine epsilon \u2014 no learning of long-range dependencies. Feedforward networks have architectural mitigations (ResNet skip connections, BatchNorm, careful init); vanilla RNNs have none. LSTM solves this by routing long-term information through the cell state via addition, where \u2202c\u209c/\u2202c\u209c\u208b\u2081 = f\u209c (the forget gate) rather than W\u2095\u2095\u1d40.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain LSTM's cell state and why it enables long-range memory.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">LSTM adds a cell state c\u209c that runs as a separate vector alongside the hidden state h\u209c. The update equation is: c\u209c = f\u209c \u2299 c\u209c\u208b\u2081 + i\u209c \u2299 c\u0303\u209c \u2014 element-wise multiplication by the forget gate, then addition of new candidate values. The key: gradient of loss w.r.t. c\u209c\u208b\u2081 involves \u2202c\u209c/\u2202c\u209c\u208b\u2081 = f\u209c. This is element-wise multiplication by a learned gate value (0\u20131), not matrix multiplication by W\u2095\u2095. The gate values are learned independently per cell dimension, and when the network needs to remember something long-term, it learns to set f\u209c\u22481 for those dimensions \u2014 maintaining near-unit gradient through hundreds of timesteps. The cell state is a \"gradient highway\" that bypasses the multiplicative recurrence that kills vanilla RNN gradients.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When would you still use an RNN in 2024 instead of a Transformer?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Honest answer: rarely for NLP. Transformers dominate on benchmark tasks. Three legitimate use cases for RNNs: (1) Streaming/online prediction \u2014 if you must produce output after seeing each token with no lookahead, RNNs process tokens sequentially with O(1) time per step. Transformers need the full sequence or use KV caching which has its own overhead. (2) Very long sequences \u2014 attention is O(n\u00b2) in memory. A sequence of 100,000 timesteps is infeasible for standard Transformers. RNNs process it in O(n) memory. (3) Deployment on constrained devices \u2014 LSTM inference on a microcontroller is feasible; Transformer inference typically isn't. For time series (not NLP): LSTMs remain competitive with Transformer-based models on many forecasting benchmarks, especially with small datasets where Transformers' data hunger is a problem.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "dl_attention": "<main>\n<h1>Attention Mechanisms</h1>\n\n<div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n  <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n  <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-why\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Why attention was invented</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The bottleneck problem in seq2seq models</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-concept\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The attention concept</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Query, Key, Value \u2014 the retrieval analogy</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-scaled\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Scaled dot-product attention</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The math \u2014 why divide by \u221ad\u2096</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-self\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Self-attention</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Every token attending to every other token</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-multihead\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Multi-head attention</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why one attention isn't enough</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-pos\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Positional encoding</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why attention is order-blind without it</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-masking\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Attention masking</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Padding mask vs causal mask</span></div></div>\n    <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"att-transformer\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Transformer overview</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">How it all fits together \u2014 see GenAI notes for depth</span></div></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Why attention:</strong> seq2seq RNNs compressed the entire input sequence into a single fixed-size context vector \u2014 a bottleneck. Long inputs had their early information lost. Attention lets the decoder look back at every encoder hidden state directly at each decode step, weighted by relevance. No bottleneck.</li>\n    <li><strong>QKV:</strong> every input token produces three vectors \u2014 Query (what I'm looking for), Key (what I have to offer), Value (what I actually provide when selected). Attention score = softmax(QK\u1d40/\u221ad\u2096) \u00d7 V. The scores tell you how much each value to mix in.</li>\n    <li><strong>Why \u221ad\u2096:</strong> dot products of high-dimensional vectors have large magnitude \u2014 their variance scales with d\u2096. Without scaling, the softmax receives large inputs, saturates to near-one-hot, and produces vanishing gradients. Dividing by \u221ad\u2096 keeps variance at 1.</li>\n    <li><strong>Self-attention:</strong> Q, K, V all come from the same sequence. Every token attends to every other token (O(n\u00b2)). Directly models any pairwise relationship regardless of distance. \"bank\" attends directly to \"river\" 20 tokens away \u2014 no gradient propagation through those 20 steps.</li>\n    <li><strong>Multi-head:</strong> run h attention heads in parallel with different Q, K, V projection matrices. Concatenate outputs, project down. Each head can learn a different type of relationship: one head for syntax, one for coreference, one for semantic similarity. Single-head attention is forced to average across all relationship types.</li>\n    <li><strong>Positional encoding:</strong> attention has no notion of order \u2014 shuffling input tokens produces the same attention scores (just shuffled). Add position-dependent vectors to token embeddings before attention. Sinusoidal encoding: PE(pos, 2i) = sin(pos/10000^(2i/d)), PE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(...). Learnable positional embeddings are now more common (BERT, GPT).</li>\n    <li><strong>Causal mask:</strong> in autoregressive generation, token at position t cannot attend to positions t+1, t+2, ... (future tokens). Mask those positions with \u2212\u221e before softmax \u2014 they become 0 after softmax. Padding mask: similarly, masked padding tokens should not contribute to attention.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 01. WHY \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-why\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Why Attention Was Invented</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 the seq2seq bottleneck</span>\n  <p>In 2014, the best machine translation models were encoder-decoder RNNs. The encoder read the full input sentence and compressed it into a single fixed-size vector \u2014 the context vector. The decoder then generated the output from that single vector.<br><br>\n  The bottleneck problem: a single vector must represent the entire meaning of a sentence that might be 50+ words long. Short sentences: fine. Long sentences: the encoder runs out of capacity, early words are forgotten, translations degrade. A French sentence of 30 words must be compressed into, say, a 512-dimensional vector. Information is irrecoverably lost.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the attention solution (Bahdanau, 2014)</span>\n  <p>Instead of compressing to one vector, let the decoder look at all encoder hidden states at each decode step. At decode step t, compute a score for each encoder hidden state measuring how relevant it is to generating the current output token. Normalise scores to weights via softmax. Take a weighted sum of encoder states \u2014 a \"context vector\" specific to this decode step.<br><br>\n  The decoder can now attend to the relevant part of the input for each output token: when generating a translated noun, attend to the input noun; when generating a verb, attend to the input verb. No bottleneck, no forgetting.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 02. QKV \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-concept\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>The Attention Concept \u2014 Query, Key, Value</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the QKV abstraction</span>\n  <p>Modern attention is formulated with three matrices per attention layer, derived from learned linear projections of the input:<br><br>\n  <strong>Query (Q):</strong> represents \"what I am looking for.\" The current token's question.<br>\n  <strong>Key (K):</strong> represents \"what I have to offer.\" Each token broadcasting its identity.<br>\n  <strong>Value (V):</strong> represents \"what I actually provide when selected.\" The information content.<br><br>\n  The attention process: compute compatibility between each Query and all Keys \u2192 normalise to get weights \u2192 take weighted sum of Values.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">ANALOGY \u2014 a search engine</span>\n  <p>You type a search query (Q). The search engine has an index of document titles (K) and document contents (V). It computes how well your query matches each title (Q\u00b7K score), ranks results by score (softmax), and returns a weighted mix of document contents (weighted sum of V) \u2014 more weight to documents whose titles matched better.<br><br>\n  In self-attention: every word is simultaneously a searcher (has a Query), an item in the index (has a Key), and a content provider (has a Value). Every word searches for information from every other word simultaneously.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 03. SCALED DOT-PRODUCT \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-scaled\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Scaled Dot-Product Attention</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the full equation</span>\n  <p><strong>Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(QK\u1d40 / \u221ad\u2096) \u00b7 V</strong><br><br>\n  Where Q \u2208 \u211d\u207f\u02e3\u1d48\u1d4f, K \u2208 \u211d\u207f\u02e3\u1d48\u1d4f, V \u2208 \u211d\u207f\u02e3\u1d48\u1d5b, and n = sequence length, d\u2096 = key dimension, d\u1d65 = value dimension.<br><br>\n  Step by step:<br>\n  1. QK\u1d40: compute all pairwise dot products \u2192 n\u00d7n score matrix. Score[i,j] = how much token i attends to token j.<br>\n  2. / \u221ad\u2096: scale down to prevent saturation.<br>\n  3. softmax(row-wise): convert each row to a probability distribution (attention weights).<br>\n  4. \u00d7 V: weighted sum of value vectors \u2192 n\u00d7d\u1d65 output.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY divide by \u221ad\u2096 \u2014 the variance argument</span>\n  <p>If Q and K have entries drawn from a distribution with mean 0 and variance 1, their dot product Q\u1d62K\u2c7c is a sum of d\u2096 products \u2014 its variance is d\u2096. Standard deviation is \u221ad\u2096. For large d\u2096 (e.g. 512), dot products have magnitude ~\u221a512 \u2248 22. Feeding values of magnitude 22 into softmax: the function becomes very sharp (near one-hot) because e\u00b2\u00b2 is astronomically larger than e\u00b9. The gradient of a near-one-hot softmax is nearly zero \u2014 vanishing gradients during training. Dividing by \u221ad\u2096 restores variance to 1 and keeps softmax in a useful gradient regime.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 attention is O(n\u00b2) in memory, not just time</span>\n  <p>The n\u00d7n score matrix must be stored in memory. For n=1000 tokens with 12 attention heads and float32: 1000 \u00d7 1000 \u00d7 12 \u00d7 4 bytes = 48 MB per layer, per batch element. With batch size 32 and 12 layers: 18 GB for attention scores alone. This is why Transformer context length was historically limited to 512\u20132048 tokens, and why \"long context\" models (100K+ tokens) require efficient attention variants (FlashAttention, sliding window attention).</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 04. SELF-ATTENTION \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-self\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Self-Attention</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 every token attends to every other token</span>\n  <p>In self-attention, Q, K, and V all come from the same input sequence via learned linear projections:<br>\n  Q = XW\u1d60, K = XW\u1d37, V = XW\u1d5b, where X is the input (n \u00d7 d_model).<br><br>\n  Every token in the sequence simultaneously queries every other token. The output for each token is a weighted combination of all token values \u2014 where weights reflect semantic relevance. \"The bank by the river\" \u2014 \"bank\" attends to \"river\" (high attention weight) and learns it's a geographical bank, not a financial one. This disambiguation happens in one forward pass, with a direct connection between \"bank\" and \"river\" regardless of their distance.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW self-attention captures dependencies that RNNs struggle with</span>\n  <p>In an RNN, the relationship between word 1 and word 50 requires the gradient to propagate back through 49 intermediate steps \u2014 and we've seen how badly that degrades. In self-attention, word 1 and word 50 are directly connected in the attention score matrix \u2014 the gradient path is length 1. Any two tokens interact in O(1) steps regardless of sequence length. This is why Transformers model long-range dependencies far better than RNNs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 05. MULTI-HEAD \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-multihead\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Multi-Head Attention</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 single attention head is forced to average everything</span>\n  <p>A word like \"bank\" has multiple relationships simultaneously: it relates to \"river\" geographically, to \"steep\" syntactically (it's the subject of \"is steep\"), to \"a\" as a determiner. A single attention head must represent all these relationships in one set of attention weights \u2014 they interfere with each other. Multi-head attention runs h independent attention functions in parallel, each with different learned Q, K, V projections. Each head specialises in a different type of relationship.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 the computation</span>\n  <p>For each head i = 1..h:<br>\n  head\u1d62 = Attention(QW\u1d62\u1d60, KW\u1d62\u1d37, VW\u1d62\u1d5b)<br><br>\n  Concatenate all heads: MultiHead = Concat(head\u2081, ..., head\u2095)<br>\n  Project back to model dimension: output = MultiHead \u00b7 W\u1d3c<br><br>\n  Typical: 8 or 12 heads, each with d\u2096 = d_model/h. Total parameters \u2248 same as single-head attention at d_model dimensions. The heads don't add cost \u2014 they work on smaller subspaces.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 06. POSITIONAL ENCODING \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-pos\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Positional Encoding</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHY \u2014 attention is permutation-invariant without position information</span>\n  <p>Self-attention computes scores from dot products of token vectors. If you shuffle the input tokens, the attention scores are just shuffled \u2014 the same scores, rearranged. The model has no idea which token came first. \"Dog bites man\" and \"Man bites dog\" produce identical attention patterns for each token pair, just reordered. The meaning is different; the scores are not. Position information must be explicitly injected.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 sinusoidal and learned encodings</span>\n  <p><strong>Sinusoidal (original Transformer):</strong> add a position-specific vector to each token embedding before the first attention layer. PE(pos, 2i) = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model)). PE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model)). Different frequencies for different dimensions. These encodings are fixed (not learned) and can extrapolate to sequence lengths longer than seen in training.<br><br>\n  <strong>Learned positional embeddings (BERT, GPT):</strong> treat positions as a vocabulary \u2014 a learned embedding per position index. Simple, effective, but cannot extrapolate beyond the maximum training length. Most modern LLMs use rotary positional embeddings (RoPE) or ALiBi instead \u2014 relative position encodings that extrapolate better.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 07. MASKING \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-masking\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Attention Masking</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHAT \u2014 two types of masks</span>\n  <p><strong>Padding mask:</strong> input sequences in a batch have different lengths, padded to the same length with zeros. The model should not attend to padding tokens \u2014 they carry no information. Mask padding positions to \u2212\u221e before softmax \u2192 0 attention weight after softmax.<br><br>\n  <strong>Causal mask (look-ahead mask):</strong> in autoregressive generation (GPT-style), when predicting token t, the model must not see tokens t+1, t+2, ... \u2014 those are the future tokens it's supposed to predict. Apply an upper-triangular matrix of \u2212\u221e to the attention scores \u2014 positions above the diagonal (future) become 0 after softmax. Lower triangle (past) remains unmasked.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout intu\">\n  <span class=\"label\">HOW masking works mechanically</span>\n  <p>Before softmax: score[i,j] = Q\u1d62K\u2c7c\u1d40 / \u221ad\u2096. For masked position j: score[i,j] = \u2212\u221e. After softmax: e^(\u2212\u221e) = 0. The attention weight for the masked position is exactly zero \u2014 it contributes nothing to the weighted sum of values. This is the only correct way to apply masking (modifying the scores pre-softmax, not the weights post-softmax).</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550 08. TRANSFORMER OVERVIEW \u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n<h2 id=\"att-transformer\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Transformer Overview</h2>\n\n<div class=\"callout def\">\n  <span class=\"label\">WHERE THIS FITS \u2014 link to GenAI notes for full depth</span>\n  <p>The full Transformer architecture (encoder, decoder, cross-attention, feed-forward sublayers, layer norm, residual connections) is covered in depth in the <strong>GenAI \u2192 Transformers</strong> note. This section gives the structural overview for completeness.<br><br>\n  <strong>Transformer encoder block:</strong> Multi-head self-attention \u2192 Add &amp; LayerNorm \u2192 Feed-forward (2 linear layers + ReLU) \u2192 Add &amp; LayerNorm. Stack N times (typically 6\u201312).<br><br>\n  <strong>Transformer decoder block:</strong> Masked multi-head self-attention (causal) \u2192 Add &amp; LayerNorm \u2192 Cross-attention (Q from decoder, K&amp;V from encoder) \u2192 Add &amp; LayerNorm \u2192 Feed-forward \u2192 Add &amp; LayerNorm.<br><br>\n  <strong>Why residual connections + LayerNorm:</strong> same gradient highway benefit as ResNet \u2014 allows very deep stacking. LayerNorm (normalises across feature dimension, not batch) is more stable than BatchNorm for variable-length sequences where batch statistics are ill-defined.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"callout trap\">\n  <span class=\"label\">TRAP \u2014 LayerNorm vs BatchNorm in Transformers</span>\n  <p>BatchNorm normalises across the batch dimension at each feature position. For sequences: different positions in a batch may have very different statistical properties (some are padding, some are content). BatchNorm would mix these, producing wrong normalisation. LayerNorm normalises each token's feature vector independently \u2014 no cross-batch or cross-position statistics. It works correctly for sequences and is sequence-length agnostic. All Transformer variants use LayerNorm, not BatchNorm.</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- Q&A -->\n<h2 id=\"att-qa\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n<div class=\"qa-head\">\n  <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n  <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n</div>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What problem does attention solve that seq2seq RNNs couldn't?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Seq2seq RNNs compress the entire input into a single fixed-size context vector \u2014 the encoder's final hidden state. This is a hard information bottleneck: a 50-word sentence must be compressed into, say, 512 numbers. Early words in long sequences are underrepresented because the RNN struggles to maintain information across many timesteps. Attention eliminates this bottleneck: at each decode step, the decoder directly computes a relevance score against all encoder hidden states (not just the final one), takes a weighted sum, and gets a step-specific context vector focused on the relevant parts of the input. The decoder \"looks back\" at the full input rather than relying on a compressed summary.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain the Q, K, V formulation. Why three separate matrices?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Query (Q): what the current token is looking for \u2014 its information request. Key (K): what each token is advertising \u2014 its identity for matching. Value (V): what each token provides when selected \u2014 its actual content contribution. Separating Key from Value is the critical design choice. Keys are optimised for matching \u2014 for a noun, the key might specialise in matching verb queries that need a subject. Values are optimised for usefulness \u2014 the value provides semantic content. If K=V, the same vector is trying to be both easy to match and informationally rich \u2014 competing objectives. The separation lets the model learn two different representations of each token for different purposes, increasing expressiveness without increasing sequence length.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does multi-head attention work better than single-head?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A single attention head computes one set of attention weights \u2014 a single mixture of value vectors. A word with multiple simultaneous relationships (syntactic, semantic, coreference) must represent all of them in one attention distribution, which averages or compromises across relationship types. Multi-head attention runs h independent attention operations in parallel, each with different learned projections. Each head can specialise: head 1 might capture subject-verb agreement (syntactic), head 2 might capture coreference (\"he\" \u2192 \"John\"), head 3 might capture semantic similarity. The outputs are concatenated and projected back to model dimension. Total parameters are similar to single-head at full dimension, but the model has h parallel mechanisms to capture different relationship types simultaneously.</div></details>\n\n<details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does attention require positional encoding?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Self-attention computes scores as dot products between token vectors \u2014 the score between token i and token j depends only on their content vectors, not their positions. Permuting the input sequence permutes the attention scores identically \u2014 the model cannot distinguish \"dog bites man\" from \"man bites dog\" without positional information. Positional encodings add a position-dependent vector to each token's embedding before attention, breaking this permutation invariance. Sinusoidal encodings use different frequencies (sin/cos) at different embedding dimensions \u2014 each position gets a unique signature. The Transformer can then use these signals in its Q and K projections to attend differently based on relative or absolute position.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
});